Type of Incident:  Transportation   Date:  08/16/05  6:45AM   Location:  Minnows Truck Stop/Hwy 90/Broussard, LA  Consignee:  ExxonMobil Pipeline/Grand Isle, LA  Carrier:  Nalco Private Fleet       Order #/POO:  113675563/107/Batch ST5G0059A3    Containers:  pc 31/Senior Portafeed/SN 11799      Sales District:  V28    DAR Category:  4B     Failure Mode:  Gasket leak     Product:  Enercept EC1118A      Amount Released:  1 gallon    Hazardous:  OSHA/RCRA/DOT   DOT 5800.1 Required:  Yes  Medical Exposure:  None   Description:   Nalco Delivery Specialist Raymond Thibadeaux notified ALERT about a leak that was discovered at the top of a Senior Portafeed.  The leak had come from the gasket of the Portafeed and remained confined to the top.  Raymond called his Supervisor and a team from the Scott Plant went out to the scene to replace the gasket.  Raymond notified the State of Louisiana, per reporting requirements, to report the leak of hazardous materials. The case number assigned by the state is #05-05555.  The Louisiana State Police gave approval to resume transportation and the shipment moved on to the consignee with minimal delay.  Preventable:  Yes, by the Plant   Coordinators Time/Est. Contractor Cost:  1 hour     Action Items:  Scott Plant:  This incident has been entered on CQ1 #SMSL-6FBK8G.  Please investigate the incident and reply through the CQ1 system.

column168: On August 1st, 2005, a loader was conducting a transfer of Hydrofluorosilic Acid. At 915 AM as the loader was finishing the transfer he suddenly noticed HFS spraying out between the railcar flange and the product fitting. The loader quickly removed the air line to depressurize the railcar SHPX 206916. Drip pans were already in place to catch spilled product. Pans overfilled and HFS was spilled on the ground. The area was dammed and diked to prevent further spread. Soda ash was applied to neutralize the area. Approximately 30 gallons of HFS was released. A faulty gasket was found to be the cause of the release.
column169: All employees will be re-trained on visual inspection of all equipment, fittings, and railcars. All employees will continue to do this before every load is set up. If damage is found on any piece of equipment, fitting, or railcar, it will not be used. All damage will be reported to the facility manager for maintenance and/or repair.

column42: ETHANOL OR ETHYL ALCOHOL OR ETHANOL SOLUTIONS OR ETHYL ALCOHOL SOLUTIONS
column168: ON 08/16/2005 THE SHIPPER GAVE PACKAGE TO FEDEX. IT APPARANTLY WAS UNDECLARED. OUR COMPANY RECEIVED IT ON 08/19/2005 @ 14:12. THE PACKAGE SAT ON OUR RECEIVING DOCK UNTIL 08/22/2005 WHEN IT WAS OPENED IN THE MORNING (APPROXIMATELY 0945). UNPACKING THE CARTON THE CONTENTS WAS A LAB TESTING EQUIPMENT SENT IN FOR REPAIR.    I NOTICED ON THE UNIT 2 LABELS. ONE WAS A RED HAZARD LABEL WITH THE WORDS "HIGHLY FLAMMABLE". THE OTHER LABEL SAID: "ETHANOL ONLY". INSIDE THE UNIT THERE WAS LIQUID, ON THE BOTTOM. IT HAD A STRONG ODOR. THE QUANITY WAS PERHAPS 60 TO 90 ML. A SERVICE TECH AGREED THAT IT PROBABLY WAS ETHANOL. IT WAS NOT CLEANED OUT PROPERLY PRIOR TO SHIPPING. TO MY KNOWLEDGE, THE CARRIER COULD NOT HAVE KNOWN THERE WAS A FLAMMABLE HAZARD INSIDE. THERE ALSO WAS NO ABSORBENT MATERIAL, NOT SEALED IN ANY KIND OF BAG OR OTHER PRECAUTIONS. THE BOX WAS USED PRIOR TO THIS SHIPMENT.
column169: INFORM THE SHIPPER OF SUCH HAZARDS. PROPER DECLARATION OR COMPLETE CLEANING, NEUTRALIZING OF HAZARD IS REQUIRED.

column17: Tank Truck Transport, Toll Leasing Ltd.
column168: The trailer arrived to pickup approximately 1900 gallons of AP-205-30 gas additive.  The Trailer had three compartments 2500/1900/3500 gallons.  Upon completion of the load product was observed dripping from the shell onto the lading system.  The IMTT employee immediately placed a drip bucket beneath the drip and called the safety department.  The IMTT employee made sure the containment was isolated and placed absorbent pads around the wet product on the cement.  IMTT vacuum trucks were used to remove the collected product from the drip pan while the IMTT employee used the unloading pump to empty the trailer.  The truck was then rejected.  Note the truck was inspected and had valid VINK.
column169: Carriers must ensure there equipment is prepared to carry hazardous materials not just annually but before each shipment.  IMTT followed an established inspection and loading procedure and it appears that toll completed the requlatory required inspections however the incident still occurred.  IMTT has reported several incidents since implementation of the new reporting requirements that carriers have problems that go undetected between inspection cycles.  The incidents can be characterized as minor solely because they occurr at a facility that is prepared to handle such incidents.  If the leak was detected while the truck was in transit it could have been a significant issue for the trucking company and 1st reponders.

column42: PAINT RELATED MATERIAL INCLUDING PAINT THINNING, DRYING, REMOVING, OR REDUCING COMPOUND
column168: During a stop at a rest area, the driver was doing a routine tire check and noticed a strong odor of paint thinner at the rear of his trailer. The driver looked under the trailer and saw that the bottom of the trailer was wet.  The driver then decided he would continue driving west a few miles to the Flying J travel plaza where he then stopped his truck, opened the trailer doors and saw a small amount of liquid on the floor beneath the pallet of paint thinner. The driver had gone into the travel plaza where he bought some peat moss absorbent, applied the absorbent to the floor of the trailer where he could see liquid, shut the door and then called the spill in.    Upon arrival to the site, the spill response company put on level C PPE and proceeded inside the trailer. There was a double stack of paint thinner on a pallet at the rear of the trailer and after looking over all of the containers on the pallet, personnel were able to find one leaking container of paint thinner that was located on the top of the double stack of paint thinner.    The response team over-packed the 5-gallon leaking metal bucket into a 14-gallon poly container along with the peat moss absorbent that the driver had placed on the floor of the trailer. It was estimated that about 2-3 gallons had leaked from the container onto the floor of the trailer. Response personnel could see that on the bottom and side of the container, there was a hairline crack in the container that may have been caused from stress or heat.    Once all of the 5-gallon pails where removed from the pallet and inspected for any leaking containers, response personnel used rags to wipe the liquid from the pallet and applied floor dry to the floor of the trailer to finish absorbing and cleaning any residual liquid left on the floor of the trailer. Personnel also used rags to wipe the liquid from underneath the trailer.    The response team then placed the clean pallet on the floor of the trailer, restacked the 5-gallon buckets on the pallet, used rope to strap and secure the buckets for transport down the road. All clean up debris and PPE was placed in the 14-gallon poly and taken for proper disposal.  The elapsed time for the emergency response and site cleanup was approximately 10 hours.

As the operator entered the rear of the trailer, the combined weight of the forklift and tote caused the trailer to squat.  As the forklift entered the trailer, one of the tote supports (leg) caught the lip of the trailer floor above the tailgate.  The tote leg folded under, causing a split in the tank body at the point where the foot is welded.  The split was approx. 1/2" by 4".    The tote was immediately backed off of the trailer onto the dock by the operator.  Another operator in the area assisted in tipping the tote on its side to stop the release.  The released material was absorbed and containerized for subsequent disposal.  The remaining liquid was transferred to another tote.  72 pounds of material was released.
column169: Enhanced training was provided to the forklift operator to better judge the squatting of trailers upon entry with totes for the purpose of providing additional lift to the load.  Release circumstances were communicated internally to be used as a functional training item.

column168: This was an Import shipment of HAZMAT that was damaged by a forklift blade while loading the shipment on the truck at the warehouse dock. The dock worker had his blades raised too high and one plastic drum was punctured. A small amount of hazmat ( o.1 kg) leaked out of the drum . The drum was aready on the truck. The warehouse was evacuated at this point. The fire department and a HAZMAT cleanup company were called. The MSDS could not be obtained from the 24 hour emergency number on the   DGR/Hazmat declaration ( TEL# 011 39 0321/642211 FAX# 011 39 0321 642219) this did extend the time of evacuation. Finally the fire department used an generic MSDS which stated the toxic hazard packing group was only an "  irritant " The Fire Department ended the evacuation at this point. Also the hazmat clean up company arrived and the drum was placed in a larger recovery drum and the 0.1kg on the truck was cleaned up. This shipment was picked up a few hours latter.
column169: The contractor of the forklift driver ( GlobeGround) gave written corrective action. The all DGR/HAZMAT shipments will be double skidded and shrinkwrapped in the future. GroundGlobe will also give further forklift training so that the forklift blades do not stick out and damage hazmat/DGR.    In a meeting between Lufthansa Cargo and GroundGlobe the incident and corrective action was dicussed at great lenghts. In addition Lufthansa Cargo requested that Hazmat/DGR be handled with pallet jacks or push carts whenever possible and avoid using forklifts ( except when necessary due to weight too high or skid opening too small to use a pallet jack)

column168: While unloading his cargo at the destination facility the Covenant Transport driver found one drum that was leaking.  The driver called for a response team immediately.  Upon arrival to the site, the response team determined that one 55-gallon steel drum had a pin-hole  on the lower end of the drum.  The product contained inside this drum was Valspar Red Ryder Low VOC Paint.  The team overpacked the leaking drum into an 85-gallon steel salvage drum.  The spilled paint was scraped from the trailer floor and placed with the contaminated PPE into a 55-gallon drum for disposal.  The two drums were palletized and shrink-wrapped for transport to an approved disposal facility.    The duration of the cleanup was approximately 4 hours, from initial call of the response team to the time they left the site.
column169: A recommendation will be made to all shippers to inspect the load prior to shipment.  If the drum was damaged prior to transport it may have been caught at the shipping location.

column168: Product spilled out the trailer dome during transit from Safe Handling Inc. to NewPage paper mill.  Driver did not see product spilling.  Spilled on road at stop lights/signs from Rodman/Washington to north on Rte 202 thru Auburn to Rte 4 North. Spill was from handle side of dome lid, going into the spill box and coming out the drain tube to the ground. Spill at Rodman/Washington stop sign was largest of spill areas, about 6 ft wide x 20 feet long; at other stop and turn areas the spills became smaller.  No spill at mill or on roads leading into mill.  Driver said he noticed some white residue dried in the spill box when he pre-tripped trailer and dog ears on dome were hand tight.  Paul Turina of Safe Handling called Maine EPA to report spilled product.  When trailer returned, the dome lid gasket was found in good condition  but the lid was warped.  Dome lid was closed and tightened again and the trailer was pressure tested, holding pressure normally.
column169: Training was not followed for proper tightening of trailer dome cover using a star pattern sequence.

column168: Vehicle was traveling North on HWY 139 at mile marker 65/ According to police reports The driver of the vehicle was traveling in excess of posted speed limit and lost control of vehicle while traveling through a curve causing the vehicle to overturn , ejecting the driver from the vehicle. column169: Same day meetings were conducted at location on company policy REF: Seat belt usage  and safe driving methods/ All supervisory personnel will attend training on the Smith Systems Safe Driving program. / Upon Accident Review we did identify areas were regional response plans could be improved / A post accident review was conducted with the top management of SemCrude L.P. to possibly implement computer controlled engine techniques for all power units.

column42: HYPOCHLORITE SOLUTIONS WITH MORE THAN 5 PERCENT BUT LESS THAN 16 PERCENT AVAILABLE CHLORINE
column168: REF ITEM 30:  THIS WAS NOT A TRUE EXPLOSION: NO FIRE OR FLAME ACCOMPANIED THE UNEXPECTED MIXTURE/CHEMICAL DECOMPOSITION WHICH RESULTED IN SUDDEN BUILDUP OF PRESSURE IN THE CONSIGNEE CONTAINER, CAUSING THE FOLLOWING EVENTS.     Newsom Trucking, DOT # 1160386, wearing protective equipment appropriate for sodium hypochlorite unload, followed specific detailed instructions from consignee employees like past instruction at this unload:   Attach hose with elbow affixed to fitting in hinged metal closure of consignee concrete container;   Commence unloading.  After unloading approximately 30 minutes, a loud boom from inside the container was followed by equipment/debris on top of container becoming airborne, including the metal closure and the hose/elbow which were thrown some distance.  Driver retreated until debris settled, about a minute, returned and shut emergency switch which stopped the unload process.  Approximately 100 gallons of sodium hypochlorite 15% by weight (about 150#) had spilled from the broken hose elbow.   As driver turned off the emergency switch on the trailer, he was overcome by vapors from the decomposition inside the container which had caused the strong pressure release.  He was removed from the scene and transported to a hospital where he was treated for respiratory distress and released within 3-4 hours.
column169: Newsom Trucking (DOT #1160386) /Vertex Chemical (DOT #285290) changed procedures:  consignees have been notified that in future unload will not occur into containers which are not labeled with chemical contents identified, regardless of specific direction by consignee.

column168: Florida Rock & Tank Lines driver was traveling south on Chapel Hill Road.  As he proceeded cautiously through the intersection with the I-20 eastbound exit ramp, a 1987 VW Jetta ran the red light and impacted the FRTL trailer at the unloading heads, spun off trailer and impacted a third vehicle.  Jetta driver exited vehicle and ran from the scene on foot, abandoning vehicle.  Wet lines under FRTL trailer were damaged resulting in a gasoline spill of approximately 30 gallons.
column169: This incident could not have been prevented or minimized by Florida Rock & Tank Lines driver.  He did everything he could to avoid the incident.

column168: While Florida Rock & Tank Lines driver was pumping off a load of High Sulfur diesel, the pump outlet hose became disconnected from the outlet pump fitting.  Approximately 15 gallons was spilled.  The driver contained the spill with spill pads.  Upon further investigation, it was determined that the hose strap was aged and worn, and broke into two pieces during unloading because it could not hold the force of the pump vibration.  Contaminated soil was removed by on-site personnel.
column169: New straps given to drivers.  All drivers are to inspect equipment and verify that straps are in good condition before proceeding to pump-off product.

column168: At approximately 12:00 CST, a Werner Enterprises tractor-trailer was determined to be overweight on axles 4 & 5 at the Sauk Village Scale House on U.S. 30 at Torrence Road.  The Scale House attendant became concerned when she observed damage to the trailer consistent with a load shift.  After reviewing the shipping papers, she found that the cargo included Sodium Perborate Monohydrate, a 5.1 oxidizer.  The attendant reportedly contacted the Sauk Village Fire Dept.  The Sauk Village Fire Dept. opened the back of the trailer and observed a white powder on the floor of the trailer that had leaked from a bag labeled Sodium Perborate Monohydrate.  The attendant expressed concern that she had been exposed to the oxidizer.  At 12:13 CST, the Highway Patrol closed U.S. 30 in both directions.  The attendant was reportedly transported to a medical facility and was later seen returning to the site and driving away in a passenger vehicle.      Werner Enterprises contacted ACT at approximately 12:30 CST and requested dispatch of an Emergency Response Team.  At approximately 12:50 CST SUNPRO dispatched a crew to the scene.  The crew arrived onsite at 13:15 CST.  SUNPRO inspected the site and observed no release of materials to the environment.  SUNPRO inspected the load and found a tear in one (1) bag of Sodium Perborate Monohydrate.  The material was transferred into a 5-gallon poly pail (UN1H2/Y1.6/30) which was properly labeled and replaced on the trailer.  Three (3) pallets of product were offloaded onto a SUNPRO vehicle so that the Werner tractor-trailer would meet weight limits.  The SUNPRO vehicle and the Werner tractor-trailer proceeded to the SUNPRO Chicago Regional Office located in Schererville, IN where the load was rearranged to properly distribute the weight across the axles.  During the reloading process, a second leaking bag of Sodium Perborate Monohydrate and several leaking bags on a non-hazardous powder were found.  The damaged bags were transferred in separate 5-gallon pails (UN1H2/Y1.6/30) along with floor sweepings of the same.  The pails were properly labeled and replaced onto the trailer.  Once all packages were secured and all spilled materials were swept up, the tractor-trailer was released to deliver its load to the consignee.
column169: The shipper needs to review protocol for proper loading of this type of packaging, including inspection of materials following loading to ensure that no rips or tears have occurred.

column168: When unloading freight from trailer forklift operator discovered a pallet with pails on it and some of the pails were partially overhanging the edge of the pallet. ON THURSDAY, AUGUST 4TH TANK CAR ACFX75307 (LOAD - CYCLOHEXANE) WAS REPORTED DRIPPING PRODUCT FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE AT CSX TRANSPORTATION'S AUGUSTA YARD IN AUGUSTA, GEORGIA.  THE RAILCAR WAS ISOLATED AS PER OUR EMERGENCY RESPONSE PLAN.  CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED AND THE SHIPPER, DSM CHEMICALS WAS CONTACTED TO RESPOND AND SECURE THE CONTAINER.  ONCE ON SITE, DSM CHEMICAL'S REPRESENTATIVES FOUND THE TOP OPREATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE PARTIALLY OPEN AND THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP GASKET DETERIORATED.  APPROXIMATELY ONE GALLON OF PRODUCT WAS RELEASED INTO THE ENVIRONMENT.  THE RESPONDERS CLOSED THE TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE AND SECURED THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP TO ENSURE CONFIREMENT OF ALL MATERIAL.  UPON COMPLETION THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO DESTINATION.
column169: PROCEDURES SHOULD BE DEVELOPED TO INSPECT RAILCAR AFTER LOADING.

column168: ON FRIDAY, AUGUST 5TH TANK CAR GATSX 61985 (RESIDUE: LAST CONTAINED AMMONIA, ANHYDROUS) WAS REPORTED RELEASING A SLIGHT AMOUNT OF VAPORS AT CSX TRANSPORTATION'S BENNETT YARD IN CHARLESTON, SOUTH CAROLINA.  THE RAILCAR WAS ISOLATED AS PER OUR EMERGENCY RESPONSE PLAN.  CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED AND THE SHIPPER, RHODIA CHEMICALS ALONG WITH HEPACO ENVIRONMENTAL WAS CONTACTED TO RESPOND AND SECURE THE CONTAINER.  ONCE ON SITE, REPRESENTATIVES FROM BOTH COMPANIES FOUND THE RELEASE WAS COMING FROM THE MOUNTING SURFACE BETWEEN THE PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE - VALVE AND THE PRESSURE PLATE.  THE PRD MORNING FLANGE BOLTS/NUTS WERE FOUND TO BE TIGHT AND ADDITIONAL ATTEMPTS TO "SNUG" DOWN THE BOLTS/NUTS PROVIDED NO BENEFIT IN SECURING THE RELEASE.  A MIDLAND KIT WAS THEN APPLIED OVER THE VALVE / SURFACE AREA AND THE RELEASE WAS CONTAINED.  RHODIA CORPORATE REPRESENTATIVES MADE CONTACT WITH THE FEDERAL RAILROAD ADMINISTRATION WHO STATED THAT THE PACKAGE MAY BE RETURNED BACK TO ORIGINATION UNDER 49CFR174.50 (SHORT MVOEMENT OF THE NONCONFORMING / LEAKING PACKAGES).  ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE WITH CSX TRANSPORTATION AND THE TANK CAR WAS RETURNED TO RHODIA IN CHARLESTON, SOUTH CAROLINA.

ON AUGUST 11, 2005 AT APPROXIMATELY 07:55, PERSONNEL IN THE CSX TRANSPORTATION RAILYARD IN TAMPA, FL OBSERVED AN ODOR COMING FROM PLMX 4553, A LOADED TANK CAR OF ANHYDROUS AMMONIA.  THE TANK CAR WAS ISOLATED AND THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED TO RESPOND. column168: Driver was delivering ammonium hydroxide into customer’s storage tank and had just begun his shutdown procedures when the tank overflowed into the containment area.  Driver notified the customer, who sprayed water on the tank to knock the odor down.  All spilled material was held in the containment area.  The customer’s operator had miscalculated the space available in the storage tank and mistakenly informed the driver that the load would fit.  No evacuations were made, no injuries reported, and no complaints of off-site odor were recorded.  Approximately 5,500 pounds of product was estimated to have been released into containment.

column168: According to the information obtained the following occurred.  While unloading, one, fifty pound bag was punctured by a forklift.  Approximately, one pound of free product was released.  BAX Global personnel performed the cleanup using a broom and sawdust.  The cleanup materials and damaged bag were placed into a recovery drum which will be held at the BAX Global facility pending disposal coordination.  The remainder of the shipment was returned to the shipper.  No injuries or exposures were reported.  The MSDS was requested and received.  All federal, state and local regulatory agencies were notified.
column169: Since the release was accidental and the result of a puncture by a forklift, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.

column168: A BNSF SWITCHMAN IN RAILYARD REPROTED PRODUCT ODOR EMANATING FROM ENTRAINED TILX 290318 AND THEN OBSERVED PRODUCT LEAKING FROM ITS MANWAY AREA.  LOCAL F.D. CALLED AND THE REMAINDER OF THE INBOUND TRAIN WAS MOVED; THEREBY ISOLATING THE AREA AROUND TILX 290318.  THE INITIAL DETERMINATION OF A POSSIBLE PRODUCT OVERLOAD IN TILX 290318 WAS MADE.  SHIPPER ARRANGED TO OFF LOAD SOME PRODUCT INTO A TANKER TRUCK.  3276 GALLONS WERE REPORTED OFF LOADED INTO THE TANKER TRUCK WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.  THE F.D. APPLIED FOAM TO THE SPILLAGE AREA AND DEPARTED THE SITE AFTER PRODUCT TRANSFER WAS ACCOMPLISHED.  YARD OPERATIONS IN THE AREA RESUMED AT 1800 HRS. CDT, 8/07/05.  GATX MOBILE REPAIR UNIT WAS CALLED TO INSPECT TILX 290318 AND ON 8/08 THEY REPORTED THAT THE 3 INCH LIQUID EDUCTION VALVE CLOSURE PLUG WAS FINGER LOOSE.  A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT WAS STILL DRIPPING FROM THE EDUCTION VALVE AREA.  IT APPEARED THAT THE PRODUCT MAY HAVE BYPASSED THIS CLOSED JAMESBURY BALL VALVE.  THE PLUG WAS TOOL TIGHTENED AND NO FURTHER PRODUCT DRIPS EVIDENT.  SECUREMENT WAS COMPLETED BY NOON, 8/08.  ALL SPILLAGE EVAPORATED.
column169: ENSURE SHIPPER'S PRE-TRIP INSPECTION PROCESS IS FULLY IMPLEMENTED AND VALIDATED AS IT RELATES TO THE MECHANICAL FITNESS AND SECUREMENT OF ALL VALVES AND FITTINGS.

column168: According to the information obtained the following occurred.  While making a delivery at PSSI Tyson Meats in Dakota City, NE a PSSI Tyson Meats employee ran over the delivery hose with a plastic garbage cart causing damage to a PVC line on the building.  Approximately 50 gallons of free product were released and affected some asphalt.  PSSI Tyson Meats personnel performed the cleanup using absorbents.  The cleanup materials and contaminated absorbents were placed into two, 55-gallon recovery drums for disposition.  PSSI Tyson Meats will coordinate disposal of the waste.  No injuries or exposures were reported.  The Material Safety Data Sheet was received.
column169: Since the release was considered to be accidental, no actions have been taken to prevent future incidents.

General Chemical, LLC was unloading ferric sulfate at the Middletown facility from railcar GATX023072.  We have an agreement with our neighbor to have our cars switched out periodically.  While the car was being unloaded, the car was mistakenly switched out before unloading was completed; therefore the unloading hose and fitting were torn from the car causing a spill of approximately 5,200 gallons.  The air pressure was shut-off immediately and the relief valve to the car was opened.  Once the material stopped flowing from the car, the car was repositioned and emptied.
column169: After an investigation and review of the incident, our operator was disciplined and received a suspension and probation.  All employees involved in unloading at the facility will received refresher training.  Our only access to the CSX rail is by way of our neighbors yard; therefore, we have requested documented procedures be reviewed before any employee enters our facility to switch our cars.

column168: ON AUGUST 11, 2005, AT APPROXIMATELY 1400, S CORALUZZO CO. DRIVER WAS MAKING A 2000 GALLON GASOLINE DELIVERY TO A 4,000 GALLON UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK LOCATED AT 700 PHILADELPHIA PIKE, WILMINGTON, DE.  THE EXXONMOBIL TANK CHART INDICATED THAT THE SAFE FILL LEVEL (85% TANK CAPACITY) LEFT SPACE FOR 2051 GALLONS.  THE DRIVER HAD COMPLETED HIS DELIVERY AND WAS PUTTING HIS EQUIPMENT AWAY WHEN GASOLINE BEGAN BACKING UP OUT OF THE TANK SUMP AREA CAUSING APPROXIMATELY 20 GALLONS TO BE RELEASED.  THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED THE SPILL AND HAD THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT SUMMONED.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT WASHED THE AREA DOWN WITH WATER.  NO PRODUCT GOT INTO ANY STORM DRAINAGE AREAS.  SUBSEQUENTLY, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THERE WAS AN ONGOING PROBLEM WITH THE TANK OR ASSOCIATED PLUMBING AND TECHNICIANS HAD BEEN CALLED ON SEVERAL OCCASIONS TO FIX THE PROBLEM.  ACCORDING TO THE WORK ORDER DATED 08/05/05, A 4" FILL CAP IN THE SUMP AREA KEPT POPPING OFF.  THE CONTRACTOR WAS TO EITHER PLUG THE LINE OR TRY A HEAVIER CAP.  THE WORK ORDER SHOWED THAT THE JOB WAS STILL NOT COMPLETED AT THE TIME OF THIS DELIVERY.
column169: DELIVERIES WILL NOT BE MADE TO THE 4000 GALLON AND 6000 GALLON REGULAR TANKS AT THIS STATION UNTIL PROPER REPAIRS HAVE BEEN MADE TO THE SUMP AREA.

column168: The accident occurred on interstate freeway I-294 at 1:15 a.m. on 8/31/05.  The driver for Split, Stanley Krysciak, CDL K622-7805-5208, rear ended a stopped semi that was in the middle lane directly in front of him.  There were no skid marks or physical evidence that Krysciak applied his brakes prior to the collision.  Krysciak was killed from the impact.  Krysciak's view may have been obstructed by the oasis overpass.  It took the local authorities almost 10 hours to remove the driver.  Krysciak had had a good driving record.  We are awaiting a copy of the police report and police vehicular inspection of the truck.  The above account is based on conversations with others and based on newspaper reports.  We believe that the tractor's brakes were in good mechanical condition and that the condition of the brakes did not play a role in the collision.  If the police vehicular inspection report indicates otherwise, we will notify you.      The trailer for Split Transfer included a total of 18 barrels of ink (appx. 500 pounds each) in front of 7 totes (2500 pounds each).  The impact from the collision and totes flattened the 18 barrels, causing the release of ink from the barrels.  SET Environmental, a first responder, arrived at approximately 3:30 a.m. The release of ink was cleaned up by SET under the supervision of the engineering firm, Burns & McDonnell.  A complete report is in the process of being prepared in regard to the clean up, remediation and test results.
column169: (1) Split has reinforced the importance of safety with all of its drivers; and,  (2) Equipment has been checked.

DURING THE SUBSEQUENT INVESTIGATION, THE TRUCK DRIVER WAS INTERVIEWED VIA A CONFERENCE CALL. THE DRIVER THEN FLUSHED THE DIKE WITH WATER TO DILUTE THE SULFURIC ACID SPILL TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL.

column168: THE FEDEX PAK, MADE OF A TYVEK, WAS FOUND IN A FEDEX DROP BOX.  WHEN THE COURIER PICKED UP THE FREIGHT IN THE DROP BOX, HE NOTICED A DISTRINCT ODOR ASSOCIATED WITH A PAINT.  THE COURIER SEGREGATED THIS PACKAGE FROM THE OTHERS.  DURING HIS SUBSEQUENT SEARCH HE FOUND A SECOND PACKAGE FROM THE SAME SHIPPER.  OUR COURIER SEGREGATED THIS SHIPMENT TOO EVEN THOUGH IT WAS DISPLAYING NO ODOR.  THE FREIGHT WAS RETURNED TO THE FEDEX FACILITY IN MADISON, WI.  THE FEDEX DANGEROUS GOODS SPECIALIST OPENED THE PACKAGE WITH THE ODOR AND FOUND SIX - 18 ML BOTTLES OF TOUCH UP PAINT.  EACH LABEL ON THE BOTTLE INDICATES FLAMMABLE LIQUID.  I WAS NOTIFIED SHORTLY AFTER THE UNDECLARED WAS FOUND.  I HAVE CALLED THE SHIPPER FOR AN MSDS.  THE SHIPPER ADVISED THAT THEY HAD NO SUCH MSDS DOCUMENT.  I NOTIFIED THE FAA IN CHICAGO THIS MORNING. column168: The hazardous waste discharge from the metal drum was due to the drums deteriorated condition that was not discovered until the leak occurred after being vibrated during transportation. The emphasis to applicable Duke Power Company personnel is to not ship any drum that they question as being suitable for shipment. If a drum is in questionable condition, it is better to repackage or over-pack the drum. If a drum is exposed to weather, personnel are to make a better effort in evaluating the drum’s condition prior to usage.

column168: OUR VEHICLE ARRIVED AT THE CONSIGNEE'S FACILITY AT 1700 HOURS AND MADE PRE-LIMINARY OFFLOADING PROCEDURES (IE PRODUCT LINE HOOK-UPS, COMPLETING PAPER WORK, GETTING PERMISSION TO UNLOAD ETC.).  DRIVER THEN BEGAN UNLOADING.  AS PART OF HIS PROCEDURE, HE CHECKS PRODUCT LINES AND CONNECTIONS, ON THE TRAILER AND HOSES, FOR SIGNS OF LEAKAGE.  WHEN HE WAS AT THE RIGHT REAR (PASSENGER SIDE) OF THE TRAILER (30 MINUTES INTO THE UNLOADING PROCESS), THE NIPPLE CONNECTING A CAMLOK CONNECTION TO A4-BOLT CONNECTION BROKE AND PRODUCT STARTED SPRAYING.  HE THEN RAN TO THE FRONT LEFT (DRIVER SIDE) OF THE TRAILER AND SHUT OFF THE FLOW USING THE EMERGENCY SHUT-OFF.  WORKERS AT THE PLANT AND OUR DRIVER USED WATER TO WASH THE PRODUCT INTO THE PLANT'S WASTE CONTAINMENT LAGOON.  IN DOING SO THEY CREATED 12,000 GALLONS OF PRODUCT OUT OF THE GALLONS THAT WERE SPILLED.
column169: WE HAVE ALREADY RETRAINED OUR DRIVERS ON SAFE HANDLING AND REMEDIATION OF THE PRODUCT.  HOWEVER, THERE NEEDS TO BE TRAINING AT USER LEVEL.  THIS IS ESPECIALLY TRUE WHEN IT COMES TO DEALING WITH A SPILL.  HAD THE CONSIGNEE CONTAINED THE PRODUCT WITH SODA ASH OR LIME THERE WOULD NOT HAVE BEEN NEARLY THE QUANTITY OF PRODUCT TO DEAL WITH.

column168: ON AUGUST 15TH, TANK CAR UTLX 11879 (LOAD - SULFURIC ACID) WAS DISCOVERED TO BE IN A LEAKING CONDITION AT MEADWESTVACO'S (CONSIGNEE) SIDING.  CSX TRANSPORTATION'S HAZARDOUS MATERIAL DEPARTMENT NOTIFIED THE SHIPPER, KERR MCGEE, VIA CHEMTREC.  KERR MCGEE CONTRACTED RESCAR, A RAIL CAR REPAIR COMPANY, TO RESPOND AND SECURE THE CONTAINER.  RESCAR REPRESENTATIVES REPORTED THAT THE CAR HAD A SPLASH LEAK FROM THE FILL HOLE COVER DUE TO IMPROPER TIGHTENING OF THE THREE (3) SECUREMENT BOLTS.  THE CONTAINER HAD EVIDENCE OF PRODUCT CRYSTALLIZATION ON TOP OF THE CAR AND THE SIDES OF THE TANK CAR WERE WET.  RESCAR REPRESENTATIVES TIGHTENED THE THREE (3) FILL HOLE SECUREMENT BOLTS ACCORDING THE REGULATIONS.  ON AUGUST 16TH, RESCAR WAS AGAIN CONTACTED AGAIN BY THE SHIPPER, KERR MCGEE, AND SENT BACK OUT TO INSPECT THE FILL HOLE COVER GASKET.  THEY FOUND THAT THE GASKET WAS DAMAGED (CUT IN HALF) AND DID NOT HAVE THE PROPER GASKET IN STOCK.  KERR MCGEE THEN CONTACTED A LOCAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR, HEPACO TO RESPOND.  HEPACO REPRESENTATIVES REPLACED THE DAMAGED GASKET, SECURED THE FILL HOLE COVER AND DECONTAMINATED THE TOP OF THE CAR AND SIDES OF THE TANK.  MEADWESTVACO REJECTED THE CAR.  IT WAS THEN DIVERTED BY THE SHIPPER TO INTERNATIONAL PAPER IN GEORGETOWN, SOUTH CAROLINA.

TANK CAR PROX 41158 WAS FOUND LEAKING BY THE MECHANICAL DEPARTMENT AT MOBILE, AL. DURING ROUTINE REPAIRS.  THEY NOTICED A FOUL ODOR COMING FROM THIS CAR AND ALSO NOTED VAPOR WAVES COMING FROM THE MANWAY AREA.  SWS, OF PENSACOLA, FL, RESPONDED AND INSPECTED THIS CAR.  THEIR INSPECTION FOUND THE MANWAY COVER GASKET NEAR THE HINGE AREA OF THE COVER WAS MISSING 4 TO 6 INCHES OF THE GASKET.  ALL THE MANWAY COVER BOLTS WERE WRENCH TIGHT.  SWS REMOVED THE OLD GASKET, INSTALLED A NEW GASKET, AND TIGHTENED THE MANWAY BOLTS WRENCH TIGHT.  THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR TRANSPORTATION AT THIS POINT.
column169: PROCEDURES SHOULD BE DEVELOPED FOR TANK CAR INSPECTIONS AFTER UNLOADING.

column168: TANK CAR GATX 66115 WAS REPORTED LEAKING BY THE M74302 AS IT WAS PASSING THROUGH THE YARD AND THE CREW SMELLED AMMONIA ODOR.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS A RESIDUE ANHYDROUS AMMONIA CAR.  A CSX SENTINEL INSPECTED THE CAR AND COULD NOT DETECT ANY ODOR ON THE GROUND AROUND THE TANK.  THE DOME COVER PIN WAS OUT AND THERE WAS NO SEAL PRESENT.  THERE WAS A STRONG ODOR INSIDE THE DOME OF AMMONIA, AND THE 1/4 INCH PLUG WAS FOUND OUT OF THE SAMPLE LINE.  SAMPLE LINE WAS CLOSED.  SWS ARRIVED AT THE CAR AT 06:24 AND THEIR INSPECTION FOUND BOTH LIQUID VALVES OPEN; "A" END VALVE PLUG WAS LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT.  THE VAPOR VALVE WAS OPEN WITH THE PLUG TOOL TIGHT.  ALL INDICATIONS LEADS TO SOMEONE REMOVING THE SEAL FROM THE CAR AND HAD TRIED TO REMOVE PRODUCT FROM THE SAMPLE LINE.  AFTER THE PROTECTIVE COVER HAD BEEN OPENED FOR A WHILE THE ODOR OF AMMONIA DIMINISHED.  ALL VALVES WERE CLOSED, AND ALL PLUGS TIGHTENED TOOL TIGHT.

WHILE INVESTIGATING A PREVIOUS SPILL AT THIS STATION, MARCUS REPORTED A LEAKING TOXIC SHIPMENT.  THE HOTLINE CONTACTED HMHTTC SPILL RESPONSE TEAM.  UPON ARRIVAL, THEY FOUND A FIBERBOARD BOX CONTAINING 4 X 1 GALLON PLASTIC BOTTLES OF CRESYLIC ACID MIXTURE, CLASS 6.1, UN 2022, PG II.  DUE TO A LOOSE CLOSURE, 1 GALLON OF THE PRODUCT WAS LOST.  THIS SHIPMENT ARRIVED INTO THE WACO STATION VIA TRUCK #5598.  THIS PACKAGE DID NOT HAVE MARKINGS/LABELS, BUT DID NOT HAVE A SHIPPERS DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS ATTACHED TO AND ACCOMPANYING IT TO INDICATE THAT THIS WAS A REGULATED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL. FILE-05-71 FAA SHIPPER-FOREIGN TRADE SERVICE AWB#-HRL 26645131343 JCC  ON 08/30/2005 AT 0042, A LEAKING SHIPMENT WAS REPORTED IN "A" BUILDING OF OUR MAIN SORT FACILITY LOCATED AT ABX AIR, INC., 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OHIO 45177.  SPILL TECHNICIAN CHARLES WARNING DONNED PROPER PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND RESPONDED.  UPON ARRIVAL, HE FOUND A STYROFOAM COOLER WITH VISIBLE SIGNS OF LEAKAGE ON THE OUTER PACKAGE.  HE REMOVED THE PACKAGE FROM THE AREA AND BEGAN HIS INVESTIGATION.  UPON THIS INVESTIGATION, HE FOUND THIS PACKAGE TO BE A STYROFOAM COOLER CONTAINING 9 ZIPLOC BAGS OF STRAWBERRIES.  DUE TO ONE OF THE ZIPLOC BAGS NOT BEING SEALED, 4 OUNCES OF THE STRAWBERRIES WERE LOST.  HOWEVER, UPOPN THIS INVESTIGATION, THEY DISCOVERED THAT THESE STRAWBERRIES WERE PACKED ON DRY ICE.  ICE DID NOT LEAK AND WAS NOT DECLARED AS A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.  THIS SHIPMENT ARRIVED INTO WILMINGTON VIA FLIGHT #132, N900AX.  THE INCIDENT WAS REPORTED TO THE GREAT LAKES REGION FEDERAL AVIATION ADMINISTRATION.  THIS SHIPMENT DID NOT HAVE MARKINGS/LABELS OR A SHIPPERS DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS ATTACHED TO OR ACCOMPANYING IT TO INDICATE THAT THIS WAS A REGULATED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.  CLEAR OF SCENE: 0059.  THERE ARE PICTURES ON FILE IN THE HAZMAT OFFICE IN WILMINGTON, OHIO.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 5:40 AM ON 08/17/05, A UN 1A1 CLOSED HEAD STEEL 55 GALLON DRUM CONTAINING A LIQUID MONOMER MATERIAL EXPERIENCED A REACTION WITHIN THE CONTAINER CAUSING THE DRUM TO OVERPRESSURIZE AND RUPTURE.  THE FORCE OF THE PRESSURE RELEASE RESULTED IN THE CONTAINER BEING LAUNCHED THROUGH THE PROOF OF THE TRANSPORT TRAILER HOLDING THE DRUM ONTO A GRASSY AREA ADJACENT TO THE FACILITY'S CONTAINMENT AREA.  PLEASE NOTE THAT AT THE TIME OF THE INCIDENT THE TRANSPORT TRAILER WAS STAGED AT A FULLY CONTAINED OFF-LOADING AREA WITHIN CLEAN HARBORS FLORIDA, LLC'S TRANSFER STORAGE AND DISPOSAL FACILITY LOCATED AT 170 BARTOW MUNICIPAL AIRPORT, BARTOW, FL.  FACILITY EMPLOYEES, UPON HEARING THE NOISE ASSOCIATED WITH THE RUPTURE OF THE CONTAINER, IMMEDIATELY CONTACTED THE FACILITY'S EMERGENCY RESPONSE COORDINATOR (ERC).  THE SURROUNDING AREA WAS SECURED PENDING THE ARRIVAL OF APPROPRIATE EMERGENCY RESPONSE PERSONNEL.  UPON ARRIVAL OF THE ERC THE TRAILER INVOLVED IN THE INCIDENT WAS IDENTIFIED AND THE SHIPPING MANIFESTS WERE RETRIEVED AND REVIEWED.  WHILE THE SHIPPING DOCUMENTS WERE BEING REVIEWED, FACILITY PERSONNEL INSPECTED THE CONTAINER THAT WAS LAUNCHED FROM THE TRANSPORT TRAILER AND IDENTIFIED IT AS A CONTAINER USED TO SHIP A LIQUID MONOMER MATERIAL FROM VISTAKON JOHNSON & JOHNSON.  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE CONTAINER INVOLVED IN THE INCIDENT WAS THE ONLY CONTAINER OF THAT MATERIAL IN THIS PARTICULAR SHIPMENT.  IT WAS ALSO NOTED THAT THE DRUM WAS COMPLETELY EMPTY AND THE BOTTOM SECTION OF THE DRUM WAS MISSING.  THE TRANSPORT TRAILER, WHICH PREVIOUSLY CONTAINED THE DRUM, WAS OPENED AND INSPECTED BY THE FACILITY'S EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM UTILIZING APPROPRIATE PERSONAL PROTECTION EQUIPMENT AND APPROVED HEALTH AND SAFETY PROCEDURES.  AT THE TIME OF THE INSPECTION, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE LIQUID MONOMER MATERIAL REACTED WITHIN THE CONTAINER AND POLYMERIZED INTO A MONOLITHIC SOLID.  THE POLYMERIZATION CAUSED THE DRUM TO OVERPRESSURIZE AND THE BOTTOM SEAM OF THE DRUM TO RUPTURE THEREBY RELEASING PRESSURE AND LAUNCHING THE CONTAINER.  THE SOLID MATERIAL WAS SCATTERED ABOUT THE TRAILER AS WELL AS ON THE CONCRETE CONTAINMENT AREA ADJACENT TO THE TRAILER.  ALL OF THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS COLLECTED AND PLACED INTO APPROPRIATE CONTAINERS FOR DISPOSAL AT A FULLY LICENSED WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY.
column169: IMMEDIATELY FOLLOWING THIS INCIDENT, THE APPROVAL TO SHIP THE WASTE STREAM INVOLVED IN THIS INCIDENT WAS SUSPENDED PENDING AN INVESTIGATION CONDUCTED BY THE FACILITY'S MANAGEMENT TEAM, HEALTH & SAFETY REPRESENTATIVES AND THE SHIPPER OF THE MATERIAL.  DURING THE INVESTIGATION IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE MATERIAL IN QUESTION IS ROUTINELY PACKAGED IN LINED CONTAINERS AND A HEADSPACE OF APPROXIMATELY 1/4 THE VOLUME OF THE CONTAINER IS MAINTAINED TO ALLOW EXPANSION OF THE MATERIAL DURING SHIPPING AND STORAGE.  IT WAS ALSO LEARNED THAT UNLINED STEEL CONTAINERS ARE NORMALLY NOT UTILIZED TO PACKAGE THIS MATERIAL AS RUST THAT CAN FORM ON THE SIDEWALLS OF A STEEL CONTAINER CAN CONTAMINATE THE MATERIAL AND CAUSE A POLYMERIZATION REACTION TO OCCUR.  OUR INVESTIGATION DETERMINED THAT THE CAUSE OF THIS INCIDENT WAS ATTRIBUTED TO THE USE OF AN UNLINED STEEL CONTAINER.  HIGH AMBIENT AIR TEMPERATURES EXPERIENCED ON THE STATE OF FLORIDA CAUSED CONDENSATION TO BUILD UP IN THE HEADSPACE OF THE CONTAINER; THEREFORE, CONTRIBUTING TO THE FORMATION OF SURFACE RUST ON THE SIDEWALL OF THE STEEL DRUM.  IT IS BELIEVED THAT THESE IMPURITIES INITIATED THE POLYMERIZATION REACTION.  IN ORDER TO PREVENT A RECURRENCE OF THIS INCIDENT, THE SHIPPER OF THIS MATERIAL WILL BE REQUIRED TO RECERTIFY THE APPROVAL PROFILE FOR THIS WASTE STREAM AND WILL BE REQUIRED TO CERTIFY THAT THE PROPER UN RATED SHIPPING CONTAINER IS USED THAT IS COMPATIBLE WITH THE MATERIAL BEING SHIPPED.

column168: OUR DRIVER WAS DRIVING IN THE LEFT-HAND LANE, BEGAN TO DRIFT INTO THE RIGHT LANE, AND WHEN A CAR IN THAT LANE HONKED, HE OVER-CORRECTED INTO HIS LANE. ALL CANS THAT BROKE OPEN, SPILLING THEIR CONTENTS (PLASTIC-LEAD SHIELDING PIGS.)  ALL CANS THAT BROKE OPEN WERE RETURNS FROM CUSTOMERS, MEANING THE RADIOACTIVE DOSES HAD ALREADY BEEN ADMINISTERED TO PATIENTS AND ONLY RESIDUAL AMOUNTS REMAINED IN THE SYRINGES. column168: OUR ROUTE TRUCK WAS WEST BOUND ON HWY 12 HE WAS APPROACHING AN INTERSECTION OF CTY TT & KANE ROAD WHICH HE HAD A GREEN LIGHT AS FAR AS HE COULD SEE.  WHEN APPROACHING INTERSECTION A VEHICLE IN THE WESTBOUND LANE DECIDED TO MAKE A LEFT HANDTURN W/OUT USING THE LEFT TURN LANE.  OUR TRUCK COLLIDED INTO HERS SHE ROLLED INTO DITCH.  ACTIOSN TAKEN WERE HAZMAT TEAM WAS CALLED IN.  THEY SECURED AREA OFF & INSPECTED AREA FOR VAPORS OF PASSIBLE CHEMICAL MISSING.  THIS PROCEDURE TOOK ROUGHLY 4-4/12 HRS.  ONCE DETERMINED THAT ONLY ONE 15 GALLON DRUM OF LINE CLEAN 3 ACID HAD RUPTURED ABOUT 1/2 WAY DOWN DUE TO IMPACT OF ACCIDENT.  4 1/2 HRS WAS THE DURATION OF RELEASE.  HIGHWAY WAS SHUT DOWN CHEMICAL WAS CLEANED UP BY ENVIRONMENT SERVICES ROUTE TRUCK DEVICE TAKEN FOR DRUG & ALCOHOL TEST & POSSIBLE INJURIES.  SHIPPING PAPERS WERE ON TRUCK WITH PROPER AMOUNTS MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEETS WERE ON TRUCK ALSO.  HAZMAT TEAM DID NOT WAIT TO GO IN TO GET THESE PAPERS ON TO CHEMICAL SPILL IN TRUCK.  EMPLOYERS BROUGHT A EXTRA SET TO THE SCENE OF ACCIDENT.
column169: TRY TO BE A BETTER DEFENSE DRIVER AND REDUCE SPEED WHEN COMING UPON ANY INTERSECTINOS.  AND TO LOOK BOTH WAYS BEFORE APPROACHING INTERSECTION EVEN IF YOU HAVE THE GREEN LIGHT.  WE FEEL ARE PACKAGING IS VERY GOOD.  OUR LOADS ARE SECURED W/STRAPS & CHECKED AT EVERY STOP.

column168: ON AUGUST 17, 2005 THE DRIVER OF A TRACTOR-TRAILER OPERATED BY BRENNTAG SOUTHWEST AVOIDED A COLLISION BY QUICKLY AND HEAVILY APPLYING THE BRAKES.  AS A RESULT, THE LOAD SHIFTED AND TWO (2) 55-GALLON DRUMS OF SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE (BLEACH) WERE RUPTURED.  APPROXIMATELY 110 GALLONS OF BEACH WERE RELEASED INTO THE TRAILER, WHICH MIGRATED ONTO THE ROADWAY, AND GRASS SHOULDER.  THE LOCAL POLICE AND FIRE DEPARTMENTS WERE ONSITE TO MANAGE THE FLOW OF TRAFFIC.  AT APPROXIMATELY 11:05 AM. CDT, MR. SHAWN SMITH OF BRENNTAG SOUTHWEST RETAINED CURA EMERGENCY SERVICES (CES) TO MANAGE THE ENVIRONMENTAL CLEAN UP ON THEIR BEHALF.  BASED ON THE INFORMATION PROVIDED, THE CES INCIDENT MANAGER DISPATCHED A CREW FROM US ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES (USES).  THE CREW FROM USES ARRIVED ONSITE AND ASSESSED THE SCOPE OF THE RELEASE.  THE CREW BEGAN BY APPLYING GRANULAR ABSORBENT TO THE FREE STANDING MATERIAL ON THE ROADWAY.  THE CREW THEN UTILIZED A BACKHOE TO EXCAVATE THE IMPACTED SOIL ADJACENT TO THE ROADWAY.  APPROXIMATELY 10 YARDS OF IMPACTED SOIL AND GRASS WAS EXCAVATED AND STAGED FOR DISPOSAL.  THE AREA WAS BACKFILLED ONCE EXCAVATION WAS COMPLETE.

column168: AT 20:00, A LARGE WOODEN BOX WAS REMOVED FROM A PACKAGE CAR TO AN IRREG CART.  UPON TILTING THE PACKAGE TO MOVE IT, A SILVER LIQUID DRIPPED OUT OF ONE CORNER OF THE BOX. ONCE DAMIAN DONNED PPE AND CONSULTED THE DECISION TREE, IT REMOVED ONE SMALL WOODEN PANEL FROM THE TOP OF THE BOX TO DETERMINE THE CONTENTS AS THERE WERE NO INDICATIONS ON THE OUTSIDE OF THE BOX AS TO THE INNER CONTENTS. THE RESPONDER CORDONED OFF THE AREA AT LEAST 15 FEET AROUND THE SPILL (NO EVACUATION NECESSARY BECAUSE PEOPLE DID NOT CONTINUOUSLY WORK IN THAT AREA) TO AVOID ANY FURTHER CONTAMINATION. column169: THIS WAS AN OLD RUSTED GAUGE THAT SHOULD HAVE BEEN SEALED IN SOMETHING MORE ADEQUATE THAN A HANDCRAFTED WOODEN BOX. column168: TWO RAILCARS WERE HUMPED INTO YARD BOWL TRACK AGAINST STANDING RAILCARS IN THIS TRACK THAT INCLUDED GATX 2818.  THE COUPLING IMPACT RESULTED IN A HYDRAULIC PRESSURE SURGE WITHIN GATX 2818 AND A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT THAT RELEASED VIA THE GATX 2818'S 75 PSI SAFETY RELIEF VALVE OR PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE.  TWO BNSF EMPLOYEES (HOSTLERS) WORKING AT AN ADJACENT YARD TRACK ENCOUNTERED PRODUCT INHALATION EXPOSURE FROM THIS PRODUCT RELEASE FROM GATX 2818.  THESE TWO EMPLOYEES IMMEDIATELY LEFT THE AREA AND REPORTED THE INCIDENT TO THE TERMINAL MANAGEMENT WHO IN TURN ORDERED ALL EMPLOYEES IN THE YARD TO A SAFE HAVEN, CEASING YARD OPERATIONS.  THE TWO EMPLOYEES WERE NOT TREATED BUT CONFERRED TELEPHONICALLY WITH A TOXICOLOGY DOCTOR REGARDING THEIR WELL-BEING AND ANY SYMPTOMS.  THE LOCAL F.D. WAS CALLED AND THEIR HAZ RESPONSE TEAM THOROUGHLY INSPECTED GATX 8281 FINDING NO SECUREMENT ISSUES AND NO LEAKS.  THE F.D. CONCLUDED THEIR INVESTIGATINOS BY 0815 HRS. CDT AND THE RAILYARD RESUMED OPERATIONS BY 0900 HRS. CDT ON 8/28/05.  A BNSF ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR ALSO RESPONDED AND WAS RESPONSIBLE FOR CLEANING ANY SPILLAGE FROM THE SHELL OF GATX 2818.

THE CAR WAS LOADED WITH ANHYDROUS AMMONIA.  THERE WERE NO NOTICEABLE VAPORS NOR ANY HISSING SOUND COMING FROM THE CAR.  IT WAS MISTING RAIN AT THE TIME.  CSXT'S HAZARDOUS MATERIAL DEPARTMENT RESPONDED AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO INSPECT THE CAR AND REPAIR ANY LEAKS.  THE CONTRACTOR FOUND A SMALL VAPOR LEAK COMING FROM THE BASE OF THE FLANGE OF THE B END LIQUID VALVE WHERE THE VALVE WAS BOLTED ONTO THE PRESSURE PLATE.  THE SHIPPER, TERRA INTERNATIONAL CANADA WAS NOTIFIED THROUGH CANUTEC.  THE CONTRATOR ATTEMPTED TO TIGHTEN THE LIQUID VALVE FLANGE BOLTS AND WAS ABLE TO SNUG UP 2 OF THE BOLTS.  THE VAPOR LEAK STOPPED.  THE CAR WAS THEN RELEASED TO CONTINUE TO DESTINATION.  THE SHIPPER AND THE CONSIGNEE WAS ADVISED OF THE CAUSE OF THE VAPOR RELEASE AND ACTIONS TAKEN TO STOP IT.

TANK CAR, ACFX 82824 WAS REPORTED TO BE LEAKING PRODUCT FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE AT CSX TRANSPORTATION'S RAIL YARD IN RUSSELL, KY.  THE CAR HAS TWO COMPARTMENTS.  COMPARTMENT 1 CONTAINED XYLENE AND COMPARTMENT 2 CONTAINED TOLUENE.  THE SHIPPER, MARATHON ASHLAND PETROLEUM LLC WAS NOTIFIED BY THE YARD AND RESPONDED PERSONNEL TO REPAIR THE LEAK.  MARATHON ASHLAND ADVISED THAT THE LEAK WAS A SMALL DRIP FROM AROUND THE THREADS ON THE AUXILIARY BALL VALVE ATTACHED TO THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE ON COMPARTMENT 2 (TOLUENE.)  THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE OPERATING HANDLE WAS HANGING DOWN AGAINST THE SECUREMENT PIN INDICATING THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WAS OPEN SLIGHTLY.  PRODUCT FILLED THE BOTTOM OUTLET EXTENSION PIPE AND WORKED ITS WAY AROUND THE THREADS WHERE THE AUXILIARY VALVE ATTACHED TO THE EXTENSION PIPE.  THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE HANDLE WAS PUSHED UP CLOSING THE VALVE.  THE LEAK STOPPED.  THEY ESTIMATED ABOUT 1 CUP OF PRODUCT WAS RELEASED.  MARATHON ASHLAND HAD THE CAR MOVED A SHORT DISTANCE BACK TO THEIR FACILITY SO THAT THEY COULD UNLOAD THE CAR TO INSPECT THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE FOR POSSIBLE DEFECTS.
column169: ALL RAIL CARS SHOULD BE OBSERVED AND INSPECTED BEFORE OFFERING FOR TRANSPORTATION.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 1315HRS, CSX TRANSPORTATION'S TRAIN, Y10425 DERAILED 2 TANK CARS IN JACKSONVILLE, FL, NEAR MILE POST SP638 ON THE FOOD FAIR LEAD, NEAR ELLIS STREET.  THE MAINLINE TRACK WAS NOT AFFECTED.  THE TANK CARS DERAILED WERE A UTLX 67446, RESIDUE, LAST CONTAINED, ALPHA-PINENE AND ACFX 79860, RESIDUE LAST CONTAINED FLAMMABLE LIQUIDS, NOS (CRUDE SULFATE TURPENTINE.)  CSXT'S DIRECTOR OF THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL DEPARTMENT RESPONDED.  CSXT ALSO RESPONDED AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR.  THE SHIPPERS OF THE TWO TANK CARS WERE NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC.  UPON INSPECTION, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE B END TRUCKS ON THE ACFX 79860 HAD SLID UNDER THE TANK BODY AND HAD KNOCKED THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE CAP OFF.  APPROXIMATELY 0.5 GALLONS OF PRODUCT THAT WAS ENTRAINED IN THE BOTTOM OUTLET EXTENSION PIPE WAS SPILLED ON THE GROUND WHEN THE CAP WAS KNOCKED OFF.  THERE WAS NO ENVIRONMENTAL CLEANUP REQUIRED.  BOTH TANK CARS WERE RERAILED BY 1905HRS.

THE TRAINMASTER AT CSX TRANSPORTATION'S HOWELL YARD IN EVANSVILLE, IN, REPORTED THAT TANK CAR NATX 17366, LOAD SODIUM HYDROXIDE SOLUTION, WAS DISCOVERED TO BE WET ON THE SIDES OF THE TANK.  THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AND CSXT'S HAZARDOUS MATERIAL DEPARTMENT RESPONDED AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO INSPECT THE CAR AND REPAIR THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK.  THE SHIPPER, WESTLAKE C A & O CORP., WAS NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC.  THE CONTRACTOR FOUND THAT THE CAR HAD RUPTURED SAFETY VENT DISK.  THEY REPLACED THE RUPTURED DISK WITH A LIKE RATED DISK.  THE CAR WAS SECURED AND RELEASED TO CONTINUE TO DESTINATION.  WESTLAKE WAS ADVISED OF THE CAUSE OF THE RELEASE.

The Nuway tanker was traveling southbound on I77 in the right lane when a personal vehicle went off the road from the left lane and lost control in the grass.  The personal vehicle slid back across the two southbound lanes of I77.  The Nuway tanker swerved to the left southbound I77 lane to try and avoid the personal vehicle and the personal vehicle struck the Nuway tanker in the center valving area.  The collision tore off the external valve and piping and also damaged the emergency valve resulting in the release of 1,765 gal of product.  Nuway dispatched emergency response crew who unloaded the remaining 1,473 gal of product into another tanker and cleaned up the spilled product and all impacted soil.  The impacted soil was placed in rolloff containers (2) and transported for disposal at a facility approved by the state of Virginia.  The area was backfilled and seeded to the standards of VMS.

column168: DRIVER LOST TRACK OF A PENITRATION POST.  DRIVER STOPPED AT STORE TO REQUEST STORE TO SCORE TWO VEHICLES PARKED OVER UNLOADING PITS AT GASOLINE STATION.  WHEN DRIVER GOT BACK INTO TRACTOR, HE FORGOT LOCATION OF A FOUR FOOT HIGH PENITRATION BARRIER POST.  WHEN DRIVER PULLED FORWARD HE HIT PORT DAMAGING WET LINES 1,2,3 OF FOUR COMPARTMENTS.  INTERNAL VALVES DID NOT HOLD BACK PRODUCT.  SEE ATTACHED SHEET INCIDENT & EQUIPMENT STILL UNDER INVESTIGATION

THE DRIVER HAD REACHED DOWN TO RECOVER A WATER BOTTLE THAT HAD FALLEN TO THE CAB FLOOR.  HE DID NOT WANT IT TO BECOME LODGED UNDER THE BRAKE PEDAL.  WHILE REACHING, THE TRUCK DRIFTED TO THE RIGHT ROADWAY SHOULDER ON THE PASSENGER SIDE OF TRUCK (RIGHT SIDE).  THE DRIVER WAS NOT ABLE TO CORRECT THE VEHICLE PATH BACK ONTO THE ROAD AS HE LOOKED UP, AND SUBSEQUENTLY IMPACTED A GUARD RAIL.  THE GUARD RAIL WAS PROTECTION FOR VEHICLES FROM A CONCRETE CULVERT.  HIS VEHICLE IMPACTED THE GUARDRAIL AND OVERTURNED.  SOME OF THE CHEMICAL IN DRUMS (12 OF 18 DRUMS) AND 3 IBC'S REMAINED ON THE TRUCK AND WERE CRUSHED / DAMAGED FROM THE FORCE OF THE OVERTURN / IMPACT / WEIGHT OF THE TRUCK BED.  6 DRUMS (OF THE 18 TOTA.) WERE THROWN FROM THE BED DURING THE IMPACT / OVERTURN.  THERE WAS AN ASSUMED RELEASE OF ONE OR BOTH PRODUCTS THAT WERE BEING TRANSPORTED.  LOCAL AUTHORITIES ARRIVED TO THE SCENE AND SECURED THE ROADWAY.  CLEANUP CREWS WERE SUMMONED.  THE CHEMICAL CONTENTS AND THE TRUCK SUBSEQUENTLY CAUGHT FIRE.  ONCE THE FIRE HAD STARTED, IT WAS DECIDED THAT THE SAFEST COURSE OF ACTION WAS TO ALLOW THE CHEMICAL AND TRUCK TO BURN COMPLETELY OUT.  MOST ALL PRODUCT AND THE VEHICLE WERE TOTALLY CONSUMED IN THE FIRE.  6 DRUMS WERE RECOVERED AND PLACED INTO OVER PACKS FOR RE-USE.
column169: AN AWARENESS PROGRAM REGARDING "DISTRACTED DRIVING" COULD BE SPONSERED BY COMPANIES AND OTHER PROFESSIONAL TRUCKING ORGANIZATIONS.  DRIVING DISTRACTIONS OF THE TYPE THE DRIVER EXPERIENCED ARE NOT UNCOMMON AND EVERYONE TAKES THEM FOR GRANTED.  WE IMMEDIATELY REVIEWED THE SITUATION AND CAUSE OF THE ACCIDENT WITH OUR EMPLOYEES AND FUCUSED ON THE DISTRACTIONS OF DRIVING AND SECURING ITEMS TO PREVENT THEM FROM FALLING TO THE FLOOR.

column42: FIRE EXTINGUISHERS CONTAINING COMPRESSED OR LIQUEFIED GAS
column168: I WAS CALLED TO BAY 104 TO RESPOND TO A SMOKING PACAKGE. WHEN ARRIVED AT THE PACKAGE I IDENTIFIED IT AS A FIRE EXTINGUISHER. IT WAS POURING OUT LIQUID THAT INSTANTLY FROZE AND EVAPORATED. WHEN CYLINDER WAS MOVED, THE MORE LIQUID/VAPOR CAME OUT. I CONTAINED THE SPILL BY BAGING IT AND PROCEEDED TO CALL JOHNATHAN GREENSPAN OF PLANT ENGINEERING TO ASK HOW HE WOULD LIKE US TO DISPOSE OF IT. HE ASKED ME TO BAG IT AND SIT IT OUTSIDE NEXT TO THE DRUM STORAGE AREA AND HE IMMEDIATELY CALLED AN OUTSIDE CONTRACTOR TO PICK UP THE CYLINDER. BY THAT TIME ABOUT 7/8'S OF THE MATERIAL WAS GONE.

column168: Our driver was entering town - 45mph zone on Hwy 54 at approximately 400am.  The road was a 4 lane highway.  As our driver entered a controlled intersection, a truck was waiting at the stoplight from the opposite direction to turn left (across the land of our driver).  As our driver went through the green light, the awaiting semi turned abruptly across our driver's lane of traffic as he tried to pull onto the on ramp going west on Hwy 94.  The two trucks collided and our driver's truck rolled over and punctured a hole in the last compartment of the tanker.  The fuel took about an hour to release.  When the emergency teams arrived they plugged the hole and cleaned up the area. The remaining fuel in the tanker was pumped out into another truck.
column169: The incident was discussed in our next Driver Safety meeting.  Emergency procedures were emphasized with all drivers and departmenet within the company.  Defensive driving was highlighted.

column168: THIS SHIPMENT WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING AT THE FEDEX WAREHOUSE.  UPON INSPECTION OF THE CONTENTS THERE WAS A 1 GALLON CONTAINER WITH CORROSIVE LIQUID N.O.S., UN 1760.  THE OUTER FIBREBOARD BOX WAS NOT OFFERED BY THE SHIPPER AS DANGEROUS GOODS.  THERE WERE NO DG MARKINGS, LABELS, OR A SHIPPERS DECLARATION.  THIS UNDECLARED DG WAS HELD AND REPORTED TO FAA AGENT CRAIG BURNS.

THIS SHIPMENT WAS IN THE FEDEX WAREHOUSE WHEN IT WAS DISCOVERED TO BE LEAKING.  STANDARD SPILL CLEANUP PROCEDURES WERE FOLLOWED AND THE PACKAGE WAS COTNAINED IN A SALVAGE DRUM PENDING FINAL DISPOSITION.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 11:00 AM ON AUGUST 30, 2005 A VAN TRAILER OPERATED BY CLEAN HARBORS ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, INC. EXPERIENCED A RELEASE OF HAZARDOUS WASTE FROM A NON-BULK PACKAGE.  DURING THE COURSE OF TRANSPORTATION, THE DRIVER NOTICED THAT A SMALL AMOUNT OF MATERIAL WAS LEAKING FROM THE REAR OF THE VEHICLE.  THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY MOVED HIS VEHICLE OFF THE TRAVELLED PORTION OF THE ROADWAY AND PLACED A CONTAINMENT PAIL UNDER THE PORTION OF THE VEHICLE WHERE THE MATERIAL WAS LEAKING.  THE SMALL AMOUNT OF MATERIAL THAT LEAKED FROM THE TRAILER ONTO THE ASPHALT ROADWAY WAS ABSORBED USING OIL DRUM AND ABSORBENT PADS.  ONCE THE LEAK WAS CONTAINED, THE DRIVER CONTACTED HIS HOME DISPATCHER FOR ASSISTANCE.  AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM WAS DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE TO ASSESS THE SITUATION AND INITIATE AN APPROPRIATE RESPONSE.  UPON ARRIVAL AT THE SCENE, THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM, UTILIZING APPROPRIATE PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT ENTERED THE TRAILER AND DISCOVERED THAT THE SIDE SEAM OF THE 55 GALLON STEEL CLOSED HEAD DRUM FAILED ALLOWING THE CONTENTS OF THE DRUM TO LEAK ONTO THE TRAILER FLOOR.  THE CONTAINER IN QUESTION WAS PLACED INTO A SUITABLE OVERPACK AND A SUITABLE ABSORBANT MATERIAL WAS USED TO ABSORB THE MATERIAL RELEASED TO THE TRAILER FLOOR.  ALL CLEAN-UP MATERIAL AND DEBRIS WAS PLACED INTO THE OVERPACK DRUM AND WAS SENT FOR DISPOSAL AT A FULLY LICENSED WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY.
column169: IN ORDER TO PREVENT A RECURRENCE OF THIS INCIDENT, OUR DRIVER HAS BEEN REINSTRUCTED TO INSPECT EACH CONTAINER PRIOR TO LOADING ONTO HIS VEHICLE TO INSURE THAT THERE IS NO VISUAL EVIDENCE OF EXCESSIVE RUST OR CORROSION.  IN THE EVENT A DRIVER'S INSPECTION IDENTIFIES A CONTAINER THAT SHOWS EVIDENCE OF REDUCED CONTAINER INTEGRITY, THE DRIVER HAS BEEN INSTRUCTED TO INFORM BOTH THE SHIPPER AND HIS DISPATCHER THAT CORRECTIVE ACTIONS NEED TO BE TAKEN BEFORE THE COTNAINER WILL BE ACCEPTED FOR TRANSPORTATION.

column168: DOT 406 TANK (TRACTOR TRAILER) MAKING A LEFT TURN ROLLED OVER, STRUCK CURB AND RUPTURED THE TANK.  A FIRE ENSUED THE DRIVER DIED IN THE ROLLOVER AND FIRE.  THE PRODUCT SETTLED IN LOW AREA NEAR SHOULDER OF ROAD, SPEED WAS TO FAST FOR THE TURN.  UNIT BURNED CLOSE TO AN 3/4 OF AN HOUR.  EMERGENCY RESPONSE WAS CALLED AND ONCE THE FIRE DEPARTMENT SAID IT WAS CLEAR, CLEAN-UP STARTED, SOME ROAD SURFACE WAS GROUND DOWN AND REPLACED.
column169: RETRAIN ON ROLLOVER DEFENSE, DEFENSIVE DRIVING, BEHAVIORALLY SAFETY, CHECK RIDES WITH ALL DRIVERS.  CONTINUE TO LOOK AT DESIGN OF CODED VESSELS AND EXPLORE WAYS TO REDUCE SURG OF LIQUID PRODUCT, BOTH FRONT TO BACK AND SIDEWAYS.  PLACE ABBREVIATED BAFFLES RUNNING THE LENGTH OF THE TANK AT 3:00 & 9:00 O'CLOCK.

column168: VEHICLE 1 A 2001 MACK TRACTOR WITH A 1993 POLAR CARGO TANK IN TOW THAT WAS LOADED WITH ALKYLPHENOLS, LIQUID, N.O.S.  THE DRIVER OF THE VEHICLE WAS TRAVELING NORTHBOUND ON FM 523 ENTERING A CURVE THAT BANKS TO THE DRIVER'S LEFT.  AS THE DRIVER EXITED THE END OF THE CURVE THE DRIVER LEFT THE ROADWAY TO THE RIGHT (EASTSIDE) ENTERED THE DITCH AND OVERTURNED.  THERE WAS NO EVIDENCE THAT THE DRIVER TRIED TO MAKE ANY TYPE OF EVASIVE MANEUVER AND THERE WHERE NO SKID MARKS.  THERE IS SOME INDICATION THAT THE DRIVER MAY HAVE HAD A HEART ATTACK PRIOR TO THE ACCIDENT.  WHEN EMS PERSONNEL ARRIVED THEY STATED THAT THE DRIVER HAD HIS ARM CLUTCHING TO HIS CHEST.  WE ARE STILL WAITING ON THE MEDICAL EXAMINERS REPORT TO BE FINALIZED.  THIS ACCIDENT IS STILL UNDER INVESTIGATION AS TO THE CAUSE AND CONTRIBUTING FACTORS.  THE DRIVER'S OF THE TRACTOR/TRAILER DIED AT THE ACCIDENT SCENE.  HIS DEATH WAS NOT RELATED TO THE RELEASE OF CHEMICALS THAT OCCURRED WHEN THE TANKER OVERTURNED.  CURA EMERGENCY SERVICES WAS CONTACTED TO MANAGE THE CLEAN UP.  CURA EMERGENCY ENGAGED GARNER ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICE TO ASSESS THE SITE WHERE THE RELEASE OCCURRED AND INITIATE CORRECTIVE MEASURES.  ATTACHED IS A COPY OF CURA EMERGENCY'S INITIAL INCIDENT REPORT.  ATTACHED IS A COPY OF THE INITIAL POLICE REPORT.

UCLX 30112 DERAILED ON ITS SIDE. A SMALL CRACK IN THE TANK SHELL APPROX. 6 INCHES LONG BY 3 INCHES WIDE BEHIND THE TANK HEAD WELD AT THE 9 O'CLOCK POSITION SOLELY CONTRIBUTED TO A SMALL RESIDUE PRODUCT VAPOR RELEASE. THIS VAPOR RELEASE DIMINISHED AND THEN STOPPED. UCLX 30112 WAS REPOSITIONED AWAY FROM THE ACTIVITIES AT THE DERAILMENT SITE AND INTO A SHADY AREA TO PREVENT THERMALLY RELATED VAPOR BUILD-UP AND RELEASE. column168: At 15:14 on 01/21/05, the Indiana & Ohio Railway (“TORY”) received from Norfolk Southern (“NS”) Form 417 (an electronic waybill) and Form 418 (an electronic data interchange) regarding the subject tanker car, PLCX 224841, which was en route to the TORY. Westlake Styrene, LP, of Sulphur, Louisiana, had shipped this car containing Styrene Monomer and an inhibitor to Queen City Terminals (“QCT”) reportedly owned by Kinder-Morgan in Cincinnati, Ohio. According to available records, at 15:15 on 01/21/05, one minute after the car arrived in Sharonville and before the TORY had actually received the car, QCT faxed instructions to the TORY on where to spot the car. Again, according to available records, the car arrived on the TORY’s line, Cincinnati Main No. 2, at 22:30 that night. Subsequently, QCT sent another fax on. 0 1/24/05 again giving instructions on where to place car PLCX 224841 on QCT’s property. The car information was transferred onto the TORY electronic information system, which uses a repetitive waybill code (“RWC”) to complete waybill forms with pre-loaded information. Due to an inadvertent clerical error, the RWC in this instance contained incorrect information, including the destination and client fields. On 01/24/05, an TORY employee caught the error i.n the RWC and corrected the RWC Code identifying the client on the billing screen and changed it to QCT. However, this change did not modify the destination or the Online Patron Report, which was generated from the destination field on a daily basis for clients and TORY personnel. According to applicable records, at 22:34 on 01/28/05, the TORY moved the car into McCullough Yard, and on 03/12/05, the IORY moved the car from McCollough Yard into Undercliff(Linwood) Yard at 1330 hours. The TORY received no further requests or inquiries about the subject car from QCT or Westlake. At approximately 18:30 on 08/28/05, the car began venting styrene as a result of the apparent exhaustion of the inhibitor and the consequential polymerization of the styrene. The NS received the emergency dispatch and responded. The TORY was notified but did not receive any 911 or emergency calls. The incident was called in to the National Response Center. The TORY obtained the bill of lading, contacted Chemtrek and Westlake for recommending an appropriate emergency response. Emergency personnel sprayed water on the tanker car to cool the polymerization process and to reduce the possibility of explosion. The investigation into this incident is not yet completed and if additional information becomes available, it will be included in a follow-up report.
column169: After learning of the incident, the TORY immediately canvassed its car inventory to confirm that it had affirmative control of the location of all shipments containing hazardous materials. Since the incident, the TORY has created a database that automatically generates a “Hazardous Materials 48-hour Report” on cars containing hazardous materials, as well as time-sensitive tabs to identify shipments that require special attention monitoring based on the commodity involved. This report is generated seven days a week at approximately 04:00. The TORY is also adding two Automatic Equipment Identifiers (“AEI”) which are planned to be placed north and south of Springfield, Ohio, by 10/10/05 to assist in automatically monitoring inventory. In addition, the TORY is reiterating in employee training the importance of recording and transmitting correct information, specifically instructing to check all fields in the electronic information system when changes or corrections are made, and emphasizing the importance of vigilance and awareness in identifying, moving and accurately repositing hazardous materials and the location thereof.

WHILE MAKING A DELIVERY OF DIESEL FUEL AT WILKINSON BUS GARAGE IN CRESSON, PE A COUPLING DEVICE CAME UNHOOKED AND RELEASED 50 GALLONS OF PRODUCT INTO THEIR PARKING LOT.  THE UNDERGROUND TANK'S OVER FILL PROTECTION DEVICE ACTIVATED, AND THE DIESEL BACKED UP THE FILL TUBE INTO OUR CO-AXIAL ELBOW.  THIS BACK PRESSURE CAUSED A COVER CAP TO BLOW OFF THE ELBOW, AND THE DIESEL THEN SPILLED ONTO THE PARKING LOT.  IT FLOWED FOR SEVERAL SECONDS UNTIL THE DRIVER SHUT OFF THE DRY LOCK VALVE ON THE TRAILER.  OUR DRIVER TIMOTHY AURANDT PA 22-711-621) LIMITED THE RELEASE TO THE BLACK TOP PARKING LOT, COLLECTED ALL THE STANDING PRODUCT WITH OUR SPILL MATERIALS, AND THEN NOTIFIED OUR OFFICE.  THEN WE IMMEDIATELY SENT A CREW TO FINISH THE REMEDIATION.

column168: CRDX 6046 ARRIVED AT ENERGY PARK, GILLETTE, WY FOR VIKING EXPLOSIVES & SUPPLY, INC.  THE SLIDE GATE WAS DISCOVERED AJAR.  THE WIRE ROPE SEAL WAS STILL PROPERLY INSTALLED IN THE LOCKING MECHANISM MOUNTED ON THE HOPPER.  THE SEAL HAD BEEN BROKEN BY ABRASION.  THE CONCLUSION IS THAT THE SLIDE GATE HAD NOT BEEN COMPLETELY CLOSED AND LOCKED INTO THE CLOSED POSITION BEFORE THE SEAL WAS INSERTED.  MOVEMENT OF THE SLIDE GATE IN TRANSIT FRAYED THE SEAL TO THE POINT OF FAILURE.  AT THIS POINT THE SLIDE GATE OPENED APPROXIMATELY 1.5 INCHES AND ALLOWED THE CONTENTS OF THE END HOPPER TO LEAK OVER THE COURSE OF THE TRIP.
column169: RECOMMENDATION: LOADING OPERATIONS SHOULD REVIEW PROPER SLIDE GATE CLOSURE PROCEDURES WITH LOADING PERSONNEL.

column17: LAND AIR EXPRESS OF NEW ENGLAND
column168: The shipment was loaded midway m the trailer. A pallet from another shipment shifted  during transportation and crushed the carton containing the organic peroxide. Because there was a wall of freight between the damaged carton and the tail of the trailer, the damaged carton was not discovered until the rest of the freight was unloaded.  The employee unloading this trailer stated that she could smell a strong odor but figured it emitted from the considerable amount of Ashland chemicals on the trailer. When the wall of freight was reduced, the smell increased and the damage was discovered. The employee went out side for fresh air and the terminal manager took her to the hospital. She was evaluated and checked out ok. The other employee used gloves to move the damaged carton and was not injured.   When the carton was located, it was placed in a recovery drum and removed off the dock. Our Hazmat clean up company arrived that after noon to pack the damaged product in recovery drums. The dock doors were all raised and the trailer was pulled away from the dock to ventilate. None of the product leaked on the trailer, dock or ground.
column169: The sole and proximate cause of the damage was attributed to the lack of adequate blocking and bracing. Land Air has an ongoing training and awareness program that stresses proper securing all freight during transit.

column168: UPON ARRIVING ON SCENE A TRACTOR TRAILER WAS ENGULFED IN FLAMES ON THE MEDIAN OF I-25 NEAR MILE POST 274.  NUMEROUS EMERGENCY VEHICLES WERE ARRIVING ON SCENE BLOCKING OFF NORTH AND SOUTHBOUND LANES, ATTEMPTING TO AVOID FURTHER INJURIES TO THE PUBLIC.  VEHICLE #1 WAS TRAVELING NORTHBOUND ON I-25.  FOR UNKNOWN REASONS VEHICLE #1 DRIFTED OFF THE ROADWAY, FACING AND TRAVELING, IN A NORTHERLY DIRECTION.  THE TIRE MARKS LOCATED ON THE MEDIAN AND SKID MARKS LOCATED ON THE LEFT SHOULDER OF I-25 NORTHBOUND LANE, INDICATE THE TRACTOR AND TANKER WERE TRAVELING PARTIALLY ON THE MEDIAN AND ON THE SHOULDER.  THE TIRE MARKS BEGAN TO CHANGE DIRECTION OF TRAVEL AND BEGAN TRAVELING IN AN EASTERLY DIRECTION, BACK ONTO THE ROADWAY.  SKID MARKS LOCATED ON THE NORTHBOUND LANE OF I-25 WERE MADE BY THE TRACTOR AS IT TRAVELED IN AN EASTERLY DIRECTION.  TIRE MARKS ON THE MEDIAN INDICATE THE TANKER CONTINUED TO TRAVEL ON THE MEDIAN IN AN EASTERLY DIRECTION.  VEHICLE #1 AT THIS POINT IS FACING IN AN EASTERLY DIRECTION AND TRAVELING IN A NORTHEASTERLY DIRECTION, WITH THE TANKER ON THE MEDIAN AND THE TRACTOR ON THE SHOULDER AND NORTH BOUND LANE OF I-25.  GOUGE MARKS AND PAINT TRANSFER LOCATED ON THE ROADWAY INDICATE THE TRACTOR ROTATED IN A CLOCKWISE DIRECTION, PUTTING THE TRACTOR IN A BROAD SIDE SLIDE, CAUSING IT TO OVER TURN.  GOUGE MARKS ON THE MEDIAN INDICATE THE TANKER OVERTURNED AS IT TRAVELED IN AN NORTHEASTERLY DIRECTION.  THE TRACTOR CAME TO REST IN THE MEDIAN IN THE UPRIGHT POSITION FACING IN AN EASTERLY DIRECTION.  THE FRAME OF THE TRACTOR TWISTED CAUSING THE WHEELS TO BE ON ITS SIDE.  THE TANKER CAME TO REST ON THE PASSENGER SIDE FACING IN AN NORTHEASTERLY DIRECTION.  THE TRACTOR AND TANKER WERE POSITIONED NEXT TO EACH OTHER AS IF THEY WERE STILL ATTACHED.  VEHICLE #1 BEGAN ON FIRE AND DUE TO THE CARGO INSIDE THE TANKER EVENTUALLY EXPLODED.  DRIVER #1 WAS STILL IN THE CAB OF THE SEMI-TRACTOR.  HE WAS BURNED BEYOND RECOGNITION AND THE CAB WAS ALSO DESTROYED BY THE FIRE.  DRIVER OF VEHICLE #1 WAS PRONOUNCED DECEASED AT APPROXIMATELY 0840 BY LUANA BERGER, DEPUTY MEDICAL INVESTIGATOR.  I NOTIFIED NEXT OF KIN, DRIVER #1'S WIFE, MRS. HARRIS.  CAUSE: DRIVER OF VEHICLE #1 OVERCORRECTED AS HE ATTEMPTED TO STEER HIS VEHICLE BACK ONTO THE ROADWAY, CAUSING THE VEHICLE TO GO OUT OF CONTROL.

K & O TRAIN WAS PULLING INTO HUTCHINSON WITH 76 CARS.  TRAIN WENT INTO EMERGENCY.  ENGINEER STOPPED THE TRAIN WALKED BACK AND FOUND THREE CARS DERAILED.  CARS DERAILED PRIMARILY FOR BROKEN RAIL AND CONTRIBUTING CAUSE OF DETAILED FRACTURE OF TRACK.  ONE TANK CAR OVERTURNED, SECOND WAS DERAILED BUT REMAINED UPRIGHT, AND THIRD CAR WAS UNTRACKED AND FELL TO THE GROUND.  FIRST CAR LEAKED CONTENTS ON THE GROUND, SECOND CAR (CONTENTS) PUMPED INTO TRUCKS; (SENT) BACK TO SHIPPER.  HAZMAT RESPONSE CONTAINED SPILLAGE TO IMMEDIATE AREA.  EVACUATED NEARBY HOMEOWNERS THAT NIGHT; ALLOWED BACK TO HOMES LATE THE FOLLOWING EVENING IN CASE OF EXPLOSION.
column169: TRACK LINES HAS BEEN REHABBED IN 2006 WITH NEW RAIL, BALLAST AND TIES.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 14:35 HOURS, ON 8/23/05 A LEAKING TANK CAR WAS FOUND IN OUR PASADENA YARD. CAR WAS - NATX 25784. LOCATED IN THE NORTH-END OF TRACK 07 IN PASADENA. TRAINMASTER JACK FORSYTH NOTIFIED VOPACK INDUSTRIES AND THEY DISPATCHED TWO MEN FROM THE LOADING RAMP. CAR COULD NOT BE CONTAINED IN THE YARD WHERE IT WAS LOCATED BECAUSE THE SAFETY VALVE WAS NOT ABLE TO SEAT. CAR WAS MOVED TO A LOCATION CLOSE-BY WHERE A TRUCK COULD GET ALONG SIDE TO REDUCE SOME OF THE PRODUCT. ABOUT 1,000 GALLONS WAS UNLOADED AND THE LEAKING STOPPED. CAR WAS SENT BACK TO VOPACK INDUSTRIES.
column169: DISCUSSED WITH VOPACK MANAGEMENT TEAM TO INSURE PROPER PERCENTAGE OF OUTAGE WAS AND WILL BE COMPLIED WITH, AND NOTICE TAKEN ON NON-INSULATED TANK CARS IN THE HOUSTON AREA DURING SUMMER MONTHS.

column168: Captain noticed damp box prior to loading on aircraft.  Box returned to cargo facility. Jeff Deitz local FAA hazmat agent notified. He conducted investigation of the incident.

Pictures (Before/During/Salvage)and copies of the reports (Fire Department/Station/Supervisor) have been FedExed to Information Systems Manager, DHM-63, Research and Special Programs Administration, DOT, Washington DC 20590-0001 and to the FAA Security Field Office,Office of Security & Hazardous Materials  Great Lakes Regional Office, 2300 East Devon Avenue, Room 223, Des Plaines, IL. 60018.    The shipment in question was being transported under Polar Air Cargo AWB No. 403-7123-4601, from Chicago, Illinois, USA to Prestwick, Ireland. The spill was discovered at the Alliance Chicago warehouse facility after it had been off-loaded from the Eagle Global Logistics truck which had transported it from the aforementioned shipper. Shipment arrived at the Alliance cargo warehouse at ORD at 11:17AM on 01 August 2005, and was transferred from the truck to the cargo warehouse, a DG acceptance check was performed on the box and no leakage at that time was noticed, the box was placed at DG area waiting for build-up to a pallet.     Shipment was overpacked in a fiberboard box, at 11:50AM when the warehouse agent went to the DG storage area to start the build-up he noticed a damp spot on the overpack, he immediately notified the warehouse supervisor, Jeff Soto, who as per procedure checked Emergency Response Guide Book and had the building evacuated and contacted the Franklin Park Fire Department and HazChem (Polar's contracted hazmat Spill Clean-up Company), this occurred at/or about 12:00PM.    The Fire Department arrived at 12:33; they 12 persons who had been possibly exposed to the hazmat were taken to the hospital for observation and released. The Fire Department contacted the EGVFD Hazmat team who arrived at the scene shortly, a test of the air in the warehouse was conducted and found to be normal, and the spill was cleaned up and placed in the salvage packaging by HazChem who took the damaged piece to their warehouse to be held for inspection and further reports by authorities.    From the reports received from HazChem it appears the safety cap on the steel drum was dented and allowed the leakage of the material.
column169: The item was in an overpacking with cushioning material by the shipper. The shipment was packaged according to the packing instruction for the material transported. As we as an airline cannot open up packages without compromising the integrity of the package/overpackage to see what is inside or if it is properly packaged according to the regulations. The only way we could have know about the damaged seal was to open up the package, and as an airline we trust our customers to give us a shipment which is in the proper condition for air transport as per the statement the shipper signs on the Shipper's Declaration for Dangerous Goods.

At approximately1530 hrs, 8-25-05 Apria Healthcare employee Richard Behunin was driving  an Apria Healthcare 2002 Isuzu FRR, box truck, ID license # KF2177 north bound on 49 th South, Idaho Falls, ID at approximately 50 MPH in the posted 50 MPH zone. As Behunin entered the intersection at 15th East he was struck on the passenger side by a 1995 Ford pickup, WY license #195CS, which had run the west bound stop sign. The impact pushed Behunin into the southbound traffic lane where he was impacted by a 2003 Honda VT750DC motorcycle, ID license number MJJ484.    The impact resulted in the Apria truck coming to rest on it’s passenger side. The pickup was in the intersection and the motorcycle was off the road on the northwest side of the intersection. The motorcycle rider, Scott Garner was pronounced deceased at the scene.    As a result of the impact and Behunin’s truck coming to rest on it’s side there were numerous cylinders or Oxygen, compressed strewn around the accident scene, none of which were damaged to the extent that there was any release of contents. The truck also contained a permanently mounted non-specification  cryogenic cargo tank containing approximately 200 gallons of Oxygen, refrigerated liquid. The integrity of the cargo tank was not compromised but due to it’s orientation when the vehicle came to rest there was a  release of approximately 55 gallons  of Oxygen, refrigerated liquid through the venting system. When the vehicle came to rest the cargo tank was sitting with the end of the tank where the control panel and vent lines are located.    Under the supervision of the of the Idaho Falls Police and Fire Departments, Apria personnel who responded to the scene collected all of the cylinder of Oxygen, compressed that had been released during the impact and those that remained in the vehicle. Once the cylinders had been recovered the truck was righted and the minor release of Oxygen, refrigerated liquid ceased.    There were no injuries as a result of the hazardous material. There was no clean up required as a result of the hazardous material release. The road closure was due to the damaged vehicles and the non-hazmat related fatality investigation.    This incident was reported to the National Response Center, case #770373, due to the initial report received stating that there was a fatality and that a hazmat release had occurred and the roadway had been shut down.

column42: NITRIC ACID OTHER THAN RED FUMING, WITH AT LEAST 65 PERCENT, BUT NOT MORE THAN 70 PERCENT NITRIC ACID
column168: On August 26, 2005 Univar driver, Kevin Wiest, was making his first of four deliveries to Ciba Colors in Newport, DE.  He backed into the open outdoor loading dock and was greeted by a Ciba Colors employee who was to offload his freight. After lifting the rear door to the trailer he immediately noticed a pungent odor and a cloud had formed inside the trailer.  They backed away from the trailer and summoned the Ciba on-site haz-mat team.  After the hazardous material response team geared up with their personal protective equipment they proceeded to vent the trailer by opening the side door.  When entering the trailer they discovered a tote of Nitric Acid had been leaking from the man way lid on top of the tote.  The lid was secured but the gasket between the tote and the tightening ring had snapped and was partially hanging out.  This is where the Nitric Acid had escaped from the tote.  The response team estimated approximately 1 gallon of material leaked down the sides of the tote, onto the trailer floor and sipped onto the rear axle of the trailer.  A few ounces of liquid also found its way to the ground.  The Ciba response team, which consisted of six men, cleaned the inside of the trailer, the top of the leaking Nitric tote and the ground below with a couple bags of soda ash.  They removed the leaking tote of Nitric Acid and the rest of their order which was 1 other tote (Cyclohexane 99.8%) to an outside location where the totes were rinsed with water.  The response team also rinsed the rear tandem of the trailer with water. When the trailer returned to the Morrisville facility it was vented and looked at by the local mechanics.    Ciba Color, requested Univar send a replacement gasket to replace the torn gasket.  Operations supervisor, Rob Frantz, was sent to the customer’s location with two replacement gaskets and a new tightening ring.  The first replacement gasket malfunctioned and snapped before getting it on the tote.  The second gasket was placed on the tote with no problem and the tightening ring was not needed.  While on site, Rob Frantz, had asked an employee of Ciba Color to weigh the tote.  He discovered even with the loss of material the tote was overweight by approximately 5 pounds.    The investigation revealed a few problem areas.  The cause of the incident was package failure.  According to Charly Bonnie the Regional Operations Manager the gasket in place was not equipped to handle Nitric Acid.  The black rubber gasket had deteriorated to the point of snapping.  The proper gasket type for this material is Teflon coated.  According to a Clawson Container representative the ring around the man way entrance on the tote was stainless steel.  The ring appeared to be worn with age but was not considered a contributing factor.   The filling checklist for tote # MV01733 revealed the tote was filled on 8/1/05 and inspected in April of 2005.
column169: Teflon gaskets and new tightening rings have been ordered and they will be placed on all current totes at the time of refilling.  The incident investigation will be distributed throughout the region in order to make any necessary changes at other facilities that handle Nitric acid.

column168: On Tuesday August 23, 2005, Daniel Jackson was driving East on State Route 188 in Coolidge, GA when he lost control of a Reeves 1993 International Etnyre distributor, unit #1114. Mr. Jackson had one passenger, Rodney Jackson, in the vehicle with him. Mr. Daniel Jackson had been working in Ochlocknee, GA and was traveling back to Moultrie GA to pump off Reeves’ distributor. It was raining heavily as Mr. Jackson approached a very sharp right hand curve.  The speed limit had been reduced from 55mph to 45mph and then to 35mph. Mr. Jackson was unaware of the speed reduction and the approaching curve. Mr. Jackson applied the brakes just before the curve (122 feet of driver’s side front tire skids were found on scene).  The rear tires of the distributor made a slide to the right and then back to the left crossing the center line. Unit # 1114 then slid sideways down the roadway approximately 30 feet, flipped onto the driver’s side and then onto it’s roof. Once on its roof, unit #1114 slid 22 feet to final rest. Approximately 100 gallons of liquid asphalt leaked out. A dirt containment area was built to stop any liquid AC from entering  the ditch.

LERCH REQUESTED THE CAR BE SET OUT AND ISOLATED FOR FURTHER INSPECTION THE FOLLOWING DAY.  THERE WERE NO DRAINS, WATERWAYS IMAPCTED OR REPORTED INJURIES RESULTING FROM THIS RELEASE.  ON 8-3-05, MGR.
