column62: Defective Component or Device; Deterioration or Aging
column168: ON 09:30 AM, ON 8-6-05, RMCC ADVISED THAT JAMES, CAR FOREMAN, REPORTED TAN CAR GATX 300455 LOCATED IN TRACK SOUTH 13, ENGLEWOOD YARD, HOUSTON TX WAS LEAKING.  AFTER BEING NOTIFIED, MGR. LERCH REQUESTED SHIPPER NOTIFICATION, MGR LERCH REQUESTED SHIPPER NOTIFICATION BE MADE VIA CHEMTREC.  MGR. LERCH THEN CONTRACTED CORY ANDERSON OF U S ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES TO RESPOND TO THE SCENE, DUE TO HIS HANDLING OF ANOTHER CALL.  MR. ANDERSON ADVISED MGR. LERCH THE CAR WAS DRIPPING PRODUCT FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET BALL VALVE ASSEMBLY AT A RATE FO 1 DROP EVERY 10 SECONDS.  THERE WAS NO POOLING OF PRODUCT WAS IT WAS EVAPORATED UPON CONTACT WITH THE ATMOSPHERE.  MR. ANDERSON IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED THE RELEASE BY SECURING A BUCKET UNDER THE VALVE CAP.  FURTHER INSPECTION BY MR. ANDERSON REVEALED THE BOTTMO OUTLET BALL VALVE AND THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE CAP GASKET TO BE DEFECTIVE.  AFTER DETERMINING THE RESOURCE OF THE RELEASE, MR ANDERSON IN COMPANY WITH VALVE AND THE BOTTOM OUTLET GASKET TO BE DFECTIVE.  AFTER DETERMINING SOURCE OF THE RELEASE, MR. ANDERSON IN COMPANY WITH MGR. LERCH REPLACED THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE CAP GASKET WHICH SECURED THE CAR FROM FURTHER RELEASE.  THE CAR WAS THEN OBSERVED FOR APPROXIMATELY ONE HOUR TO ASSURE THERE WOULD BE NO ADDITIONAL LEAKAGE AFTER REPLACING THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE GASKET.  AT 02:10 PM, THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO CONTINUE ONTO DESTINATION.  THERE WERE NO DRAINS, WATERWAYS IMPACTED, OR REPORTED INJURIES RESULTING FROM THIS RELEASE.  LINDA SALINAS, MANAGER ENVIRONMENTAL HEALTH & SAFETY, TEXMARK INDUSTRIES, WAS ADVISED OF THE RELEASE, AND CORRECTIVE ACTION TAKEN TO STOP THE RELEASE.  SHE WAS FURTHER ADVISED THE CAR WOULD HAVE TO BE HOME SHIPPED FOR FURTHER INSPECTION AND NECESSARY REPAIRS AFTER IT WAS OFF LAODED.

DECISION MADE TO TRANSFER TANK CAR INTO A PRODUCT-COMPATIBLE TANK CAR, SUPPLIED BY DUPONT, CHAMBERS WORKS WASTE WATER TREATMENT PLANT (WWTP), DEEPWATER, NJ A PLASTIC TROUGH WAS SECURED TO THE BOTTOM OUTLET, WITH CHEMICAL ABSORBANT PADS INSIDE, TO CONTAIN LEAK UNTIL TRANSFER COULD BE CONDUCTED.  AS WITNESSED TO HAVE DRIPPED (ON A SMALL PILE OF HARD PACKED POWDERED CEMENT) WAS CLEANED AND BAGGED FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.  TANK CAR ACFX 200593, IN THE SAME PRODUCT SERVICE, WAS DELIVERED TO PAVONIA YARD.  BOTH TANK CARS WERE MOVED AND SECURED TO THE "NOTCH TRACK," AND TRANSFER WAS ACCOMPLISHED WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT, ON 8/25/05.  ACFX 200593 WAS RE-ORDERED AND FORWARDED TO DUPONT'S WWTP FOR UNLOADING.  SHPX 200907 COULD NOT BE ENTIRELY CLEANED BY CONTRACTOR, SO STILL CONSIDERED TO BE CONTAINING A RESIDUE OF THE PRODUCT.  CAR LESSEE, DUPONT, WILMINGTON, DE, TO APPLY TO DOT-FRA FOR MOVEMENT AUTHORITY TO HAVE THE CAR SHIPPED FROM CR'S PAVONIA YARD, TO RESCAR, DUBOIS, PA.

column58: Discharge Valve or Coupling; Piping or Fittings; Weld or Seam
column168: OUR DRIVER, RAFAEL PADILLA, WAS DRIVING SOUTHBOUND ON HIGHWAY 101 AT APPROXIMATELY 10:30 AM ON AUGUST 18, 2005.  A PASSING MOTORIST MOTIONED TO OUR DRIVER TO PULL OVER.  OUR DRIVER PULLED TO THE ROADSIDE TO CHECK FOR A PROBLEM, HE DISCOVERED HE HAD A LEAK IN THE PIPING.  WHICH MEANT THE INTERNAL VALVE WAS NOT HOLDING.  THE INTERNAL VALVE THAT FAILED TO SEAT PROPERLY WAS AN ALLIGHENY SSE-1123 ALLOWING PRODUCT INTO THE PIPING A WELD SEAM AT A 90 SS 3" PIPE JOINT FAILED ALLOWING PRODUCT TO LEAK.  AFTER STOPPING AND IDENTIFYING THE PROBLEM THE DRIVER CHECKED TO SEE IF THE INTERNAL VALVE WAS INDEED CLOSED, IT WAS.  WHEN THE FIRE DEPARTMENT ARRIVED THEY PUT CONTAINMENT UNDER PIPING CONTAINING THE LEAKAGE WE THEN ARRANGED FOR A VACUUM TRUCK TO TOP UNLOAD THE PRODUCT.  THE PAVEMENT EFFECTED WAS NEUTRALIZED BY CAL-TRANS THE EFFECTED DIRT WAS PICKED UP AND BARRELED FOR DISPOSAL.  THE CALIFORNIA HIGHWAY PATROL INVESTIGATED THE VALVE, IT SEEMED TO BE "OK," THE SEAT SURFACE WAS IN EXCELLENT CONDITION.  THE INSIDE OF THE 90 ELBOW THAT FAILED WAS CORRODED.

ON AUGUST 10, 2005, AT APPROXIMATELY 5:40 PM, A PASSENGER VEHICLE TRAVELING SOUTHBOUND ON COUNTY ROAD 625E FAILED TO YIELD AND PULLED OUT IN FRONT OF A LLL TRANSPORT, INC. ("LLL") TRUCK AS IT DROVE EASTBOUND ON STATE ROAD 32.  WHILE SWERVING TO AVOID A COLLISION, THE TRUCK STRUCK THE VEHICLE'S FRONT PASSENGER SIDE, TIPPED OVER AND CAME TO REST ON THE SIDE OF THE ROAD.  CONSEQUENTLY, THE ETHANOL IN THE TANKER TRUCK BEGAN TO LEAK OUT OF THE FILL HOLE.  A REPRESENTATIVE OF LLL CALLED THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER, INCIDENT NUMBER 768-665.  ADDITIONALLY, THE INDIANA DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT DISPATCHED MIKE SUTTON TO THE SCENE AFTER RECEIVING A CALL FROM A LLL REPRESENTATIVE.  FOLLOWING THE INCIDENT, POLICE, FIRE CREWS, AND HAZMAT TEAMS RESPONDED TO THE SITE.  AFTER CLOSING THE ROAD, THE DARLINGTON FIRE DEPARTMENT WORKED WITH OTHER LOCAL FIRE DISTRICTS AND THE INDIANA HAZMAT TEAM OUT OF INDIANAPOLIS.  FIVE HOUSES IN THE AREA AROUND THE SPILL SITE WERE EVACUATED FOR APPROXIMATELY FIVE HOURS AS A PRECAUTIONARY MEASURE DURING THE RESPONSE.  IN ADDITION, ERS, INC., OUT OF INDIANAPOLIS, INDIANA ARRIVED ON SCENE TO ASSIST WITH REMOVAL OF THE TRUCK.  THE TEAMS PLACED SAND BERMS AND BOOMS TO THE WEST OF THE TRUCK AND EFFECTIVELY CONTAINED THE SPILL.  AFTER ERS RIGHTED THE TRUCK, ERS REMOVED THE REMAINING PRODUCT FROM THE TANKER.  THE COMBINED EFFORTS KEPT THE LARGE MAJORITY OF PRODUCT IN THE TANKER; ONLY 270 GALLONS OF ETHANOL LEAKED OUT OF THE TANKER'S FILL HOLE.  SUBSEQUENTLY ERS AND BURNS & MCDONNELL, THE ENGINEERING FIRM HIRED BY LLL TO ASSIST WITH THE RESPONSE AND REMEDIATION, EXCAVATED THE IMPACTED SOIL NEXT TO THE ROAD, REMOVED IMPACTED DEBRIS, AND BACKFILLED THE AREA.  ERS HAD DISPOSED OF THE IMPACTED SOIL AT AN APPROVED LANDFILL.  REMEDIATION EFFORTS CONTINUE TO REMOVE THE SMALL QUANTITY OF PRODUCT THAT IS UNDER THE ROADWAY.  CURRENTLY, EIGHT SOIL VAPOR EXTRACTION WELLS ARE UNDER THE ROAD TO ELIMINATE THE RESIDUAL ETHANOL.

column168: ON SATURDAY, AUGUST 6TH, 2005, TRAIN MNPPT 02, LEAD LOCOMOTIVE UP 5826, DERAILED 5 LOADED TANK CARS OF DENATURED ALCOHOL WHILE ENTERING THE NORTH END OF THE ALBINA FREIGHT YARD IN PORTLAND, OR.  TWO CARS WERE DERAILED UPRIGHT AND THREE OF THE TANK CARS WERE LEANING AT A 45 DEG. ANGLE.  THE PORTLAND FIRE BUREAU WAS NOTIFIED AND UPON ARRIVAL STARTED EVACUATION OF LOCA BUSINESS IN THE AREA OF THE DERAILMENT.  MGR. C.T.S. RICK SLOANNE RESPONDED AND AFTER BRIEFING WITH THE FIRE DEPT. INSPECTED THE DERAILED CARS.  MR. SLOANE DISCOVERED TWO OF THE LEANING TANK CARS, SHPX 206665, AND UTLX 202771 WERE LEAKING FROM VACUUM RELIEF VALVES.  MR. SLOANE STOPPED THE LEAKS BY ROTATING ONE VALVE AND USING WOOD WEDGES TO SEAL THE OTHER.  AFTER DEBRIEFING WITH THE FIRE DEPARTMENT, THE INCIDENT WAS TERMINATED.  THE TANK CARS WERE RERAILED LATER THAT EVENING.  THE THREE CARS THAT WERE LEANING, UTLX 202771, SHPX 206668, AND SHPX 206665 WILL BE TRANSFERRED TO OTHER TANK CARS.

column42: NITRIC ACID OTHER THAN RED FUMING, WITH AT LEAST 65 PERCENT, BUT NOT MORE THAN 70 PERCENT NITRIC ACID
column168: TRENT BARRETT, YARDMASTER, REPORTED TANKCAR EDCX 6035 WAS VENTING NITRIC ACID AT THE WEST BOWL.  MR. BARRETT STATED A BUFFER ZONE OF APPROXIMATELY ONE HALF HAD BEEN ESTABLISHED AROUND THE TANKCAR AND HE HAD NOTIFIED KIM KEELING, MANAGER OF ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS, MR. KEELING RESPONDED.  AN EVACUATION OF APPROXIMATELY 80 UPRR EMPLOYEES WAS CONDUCTED DUE TO THE NATURE OF THE RELEASE.  ALL STATE NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE.  AT 09:15 AM, KEELING REPORTED HE HAD INSPECTED THE TANKCAR AND IT HAD LEAKED APPROXIMATELY FIVE GALLONS OF THE LIQUID, VIA THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE.  MR. KEELING FURTHER STATED THE TANKCAR WAS ISOLATED DURING THE INCIDENT.  AT 03:18 PM, MGR KEELING ADVISED THE TANKCAR HAD CRACKS IN A WELD ON THE LIQUID VALVE NOZZLE AND THE LOAD WOULD NEED TO BE TRANSFERRED TO ANOTHER TANKCAR.  MR. KEELING FURTHER STATED THEY WERE RELEASING PRESSURE OFF THE TANKCAR TO PREVENT FURTHER VENTING AND THE TANKCAR WAS REPORTED TO HAVE HAD CRACKS IN THE WELDS PRIOR TO BEING DELIVERED TO THE YARD.  THE PRODUCT THAT WAS RELEASED WAS NEUTRALIZED WITH BAKING SODA AND WATER.  APPROXIMATELY 100 POUNDS OF BAKING SODA WAS USED WITH 25 GALLONS OF WATER.  FEDERAL NOTIFICATION WAS COMPLETED.  THIS TANK CAR WAS CARRYING GREATER THAN 90% CONCENTRATED NITRIC ACID, WHICH EXPLAINS THE FUMING OF THE PRODUCT.  MR. KEELING INSTALLED A VAPOR LINE THAT WAS ROUTED TO A DRUM OF BAKING SODA WATER IN ORDER TO SCRUB THE VAPORS WHILE THE TANK CAR WAS BEING REVIEWED FOR REPAIR OPTIONS.  ON 8/23/05, THE DECISION TREE WAS MADE BETWEEN THE SHIPPER AND UPRR PERSONNEL TO REMOVE THE EDUCTION LINE AND BLIND FLANGE THE OUTLET IN ORDER TO OBTAIN A ONE TIME MOVEMENT APPROVAL FROM THE FRA.  THE LOAD WAS RETURNED TO THE EL DORADO CHEMICAL PLANT IN EL DORADO ARKANSAS FOR OFF LOADING AND REPAIRS.  MOVEMENT APPROVAL NUMBER FRA-05080237.  ON 8/24/05 HAZ-MAT RESPONSE INC. WAS CHOSEN TO DO THE REPAIRS IN ORDER TO RETURN THE SHIPMENT TO ELDORADO ARK.  ON 8/25 THE CONTRACTOR REMOVED THE EDUCTION LINE AND BLIND FLANGED THE OUTLET AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO TRANSPORTATION WITH "DO NOT LOAD, HOMESHOP FOR REPAIRS" STICKER PLACED ON FOUR SIDES OF THE TANK CAR.  THE EDUCTION LINE, ONE LIQUID VALVE AND FASTNERS WERE SHIPPED BACK TO EL DORADO ARK.
